# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: russell-sage-foundation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The borough of Manhattan in New York City contains 214 numbered east–west streets ranging from 1st to 228th, the majority of them designated in the Commissioners' Plan of 1811.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] These streets do not run exactly east–west, because the grid plan is aligned with the Hudson River, rather than with the cardinal directions.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Thus, the majority of the Manhattan grid's "west" is approximately 29 degrees north of true west; the angle differs above 155th Street, where the grid initially ended.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The grid now covers the length of the island from 14th Street north.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] All numbered streets carry an East or West prefix – for example, East 10th Street or West 10th Street – which is demarcated at Broadway below 8th Street, and at Fifth Avenue at 8th Street and above.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The numbered streets carry crosstown traffic.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] In general, but with numerous exceptions, even-numbered streets are one-way eastbound and odd-numbered streets are one-way westbound.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Most wider streets, and a few of the narrow ones, carry two-way traffic.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Although the numbered streets begin just north of East Houston Street in the East Village, they generally do not extend west into Greenwich Village, which already had established, named streets when the grid plan was laid out by the Commissioners' Plan of 1811.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Some streets in that area that do continue farther west change direction before reaching the Hudson River.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The highest numbered street on Manhattan Island is 220th Street, but Marble Hill is also within the borough of Manhattan, so the highest street number in the borough is 228th Street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The numbering system continues in the Bronx, up to 263rd Street, though east of Van Cortlandt Park the system ends at 243rd Street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The lowest numbered street in Manhattan is East 1st Street, which runs through Alphabet City near East Houston Street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] There are also three streets numbered as First, Second and Third Place in Battery Park City.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] East 1st Street begins just north of East Houston Street at Avenue A and continues to the Bowery.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Peretz Square, a small triangular sliver park where Houston Street, First Street and First Avenue meet marks the spot where the grid takes hold.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] East 2nd Street begins just north of East Houston Street at Avenue C and also continues to the Bowery.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The east end of East 3rd, 4th, 5th, and 7th streets is Avenue D, with East 6th Street continuing further eastward and connecting to the FDR Drive.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The west end of most of these streets is the Bowery and Third Avenue, except for 3rd Street (formerly Amity Place), which continues to Sixth Avenue; and 4th Street, which extends west and then north to 13th Street in Greenwich Village.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Great Jones Street connects East 3rd to West 3rd.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] East 5th Street goes west to Cooper Square, but is interrupted between Avenues B and C by The Earth School and Public School 364, and between First Avenue and Avenue A by the Village View Apartments.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] East 6th Street contains many Indian restaurants between First and Second Avenues and is sometimes known as Curry Row.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 8th and 9th streets run parallel to each other, beginning at Avenue D, interrupted by Tompkins Square Park at Avenue B, resuming at Avenue A and continuing to Sixth Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] West 8th Street is an important local shopping street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 8th Street between Avenue A and Third Avenue is called St Mark's Place, but it is counted in the length below.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The M8 bus route operates eastbound on 8th Street and westbound on 9th Street between Avenue A and Sixth Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 8th Street has one subway station: Eighth Street–New York University, served by the N, R and W Trains.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Amos, Hammond, and Troy Streets were in the Greenwich Village street grid before 1811.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] In the middle 19th century they were renamed as the western parts of West 10th, 11th and 12th Streets, respectively.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Additionally, **Little West 12th Street** runs parallel to West 13th Street from West Street to the northeast corner of Ninth Avenue and Gansevoort Street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 14th Street is a main numbered street in Manhattan.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It begins at Avenue C and ends at West Street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] From Avenue A or Avenue C to West Street there is service M14A/D bus.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] At 6th Avenue, there is a PATH stop with service to Midtown Manhattan and New Jersey.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Traffic on 15th Street moves from east to west.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The street formerly started at the FDR Drive, but most of the street between the Drive and Avenue C was permanently closed, as was the 15th Street exit from the Drive, after the September 11 attacks, due to the presence of the Con Edison East River Generating Station there.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Only Con Edison personnel have access to the closed portion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The street is then interrupted by Stuyvesant Town from Avenue C to First Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It then continues to Union Square East (Park Avenue South) where it is interrupted by Union Square It picks up again at Union Square West, and continues unimpeded to Eleventh Avenue at the Hudson River.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Traffic on 16th Street moves from west to east.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It starts at Eleventh Avenue at the Hudson River, and runs until it is interrupted at Union Square West (Broadway) by Union Square.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It picks up again on the other side of the park at Union Square East (Park Avenue South), but is shortly stopped again by Stuyvesant Square from between Second and Third Avenues (Rutherford Place) to between First and Second Avenues (Perlman Place).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] At First Avenue, it is interrupted by Stuyvesant Town, and starts up again at Avenue C.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It then dead ends between that avenue and the FDR Drive.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 17th, 18th and 19th streets start at First Avenue and finish at Eleventh Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It forms the northern borders of both Union Square (between Broadway and Park Avenue South) and Stuyvesant Square.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Composer Antonín Dvořák's New York home was located at 327 East 17th Street, near Perlman Place.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The house was razed by Beth Israel Medical Center after it received approval of a 1991 application to demolish the house and replace it with an AIDS hospice with financing from the photographer Robert Mapplethorpe.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] *Time* Magazine was started at 141 East 17th Street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 18th Street has a local subway station at the crossing with Seventh Avenue, served by the 1 (and the 2 at late nights) on the IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] There used to be an 18th Street station on the IRT Lexington Avenue Line at the crossing with Park Avenue South.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] This street is home to the IAC Building, designed by Frank Gehry.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 19th Street travels west for most of its length, except between Tenth and Eleventh Avenues the travel direction is reversed and traffic flows east.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 20th Street starts at Avenue C, and 21st and 22nd Streets begin at First Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Travel on the last block of the 20th, 21st, and 22nd streets, between Tenth and Eleventh Avenues, is in the opposite direction than it is on the rest of the respective street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 20th Street is very wide from the Avenue C to First Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Along the southern perimeter of Gramercy Park, between Gramercy Park East and Gramercy Park West, 20th Street is known as Gramercy Park South.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Between Second and Third Avenues, 21st Street is alternatively known as Police Officer Anthony Sanchez Way.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Along the northern perimeter of Gramercy Park, between Gramercy Park East and Gramercy Park West, 21st Street is known as Gramercy Park North.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 23rd Street is another main numbered street in Manhattan.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It begins at Avenue C/FDR Drive and ends at Eleventh Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Additionally, there is the M23 Select Bus Service, running through the length of 23rd Street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] A small portion of 24th Street exists between First Avenue and East Midtown Plaza ending at a dead end before Second Avenue, a second portion is between East Midtown Plaza and Madison Avenue, ending because of Madison Square Park.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 25th Street, which is in three parts, starts at FDR Drive, is a pedestrian plaza between Third Avenue and Lexington Avenue, and ends at Madison.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Then West 24th and 25th streets continue from Fifth Avenue to Eleventh Avenue (25th) or Twelfth Avenue (24th).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The two cul-de-sacs on 24th Street between First and Second avenues were created in the late 1960s to connect the northern and southern blocks of East Midtown Plaza with a mid-block pedestrian plaza having a focal point on St.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The pedestrian plaza on 25th Street between Third and Lexington avenues, named the "Clivner=Field Plaza", was completed in 2021 and provides outdoor space for the campus of Baruch College.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 26th Street is all in one part and after reaching FDR Drive bends and runs parallel to FDR Drive up to 30th Street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Some of the most notable venues are Bungalow 8, Marquee, Suzie Wong, Cain, and Pink Elephant.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 27th and continuing down almost the entire rest of the block, the former warehouse spaces of clubs Twilo, Guesthouse, Home, Bed, and more have been repurposed by British immersive theater group Punchdrunk as The McKittrick Hotel, the site of their theatrical experience *Sleep No More*.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Heading east, 27th Street passes through Chelsea Park between Tenth and Ninth Avenues, with the Fashion Institute of Technology (FIT) on the corner of Eighth.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] On Madison Avenue between 26th and 27th streets, on the site of the old Madison Square Garden, is the New York Life Building, built in 1928 and designed by Cass Gilbert, with a square tower topped by a striking gilded pyramid.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Twenty-Seventh Street passes one block north of Madison Square Park and culminates at Bellevue Hospital on First Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The segment of 27th Street east of Second Avenue is a pedestrian mall and passes through Bellevue South Park.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 30th Street runs uninterrupted across the island from 12th Avenue to FDR Drive.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It is the southern terminus of Dyer Avenue and thus also of the Lincoln Tunnel's eastern approach.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] There is also an elevator with access to the High Line on the West Side.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Tisch Hospital is bounded on the south by 30th Street between 1st Avenue and FDR Drive.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The segment of 30th Street between First and Second avenues was widened by 20 feet (6.1 m) in the 1950s when the superblock for Kips Bay Towers was created.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] On the East Side, both streets end at Second Avenue, where the street grid is interrupted by superblocks containing Kips Bay Towers and NYU Medical Center.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Francis of Assisi is situated at 135–139 West 31st Street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] At 210 West is the Capuchin Monastery of St.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] At the corner of Broadway and West 31st Street is the Grand Hotel.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The former Hotel Pierrepont was located at 43 West 32nd Street, The Continental NYC tower is at the corner of Sixth Avenue and 32nd Street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 29 East 32nd Street was the location of the first building owned by the Grolier Club between 1890 and 1917.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] In 2017, the segment of 32nd Street between Second and Third avenues was co-named "Ms.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Magazine Way" in honor of the location where the publication was launched at 207 East 32nd Street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 33rd Street runs uninterrupted from First Avenue to Seventh Avenue where it turns into a pedestrian road for a quarter of a block and turns back into a street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Then it runs the rest of the way to 12th Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It runs on the north side of Hudson Yards and the south side of the Empire State Building.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The segment of 33rd Street between First and Second avenues was widened by 20 feet (6.1 m) in the 1950s when the superblock for Kips Bay Towers was created.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] In 2018, the same street segment was converted from one-way to two-way traffic to improve access for ambulances traveling to emergency entrance of NYU Langone Health on First Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] At Park Avenue, 33rd Street was closed to westbound through traffic beginning in 1999, when barriers were installed at the southern end of the Park Avenue Tunnel.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] In 2019, the segment of 33rd Street between Tenth and Eleventh avenues was reconstructed as part of the Hudson Yards Redevelopment Project, which included raising the street elevation by up to 15 feet (4.6 m) for integration with Hudson Boulevard.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 35th Street runs from FDR Drive to Eleventh Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Notable locations include East River Ferry, Mercy University Manhattan Campus, and the Jacob K.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 36th Street runs from the FDR Drive to Eleventh Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It runs on the south side of the Queens–Midtown Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit and over the Lincoln Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Notable locations on 36th Street are the American Copper Buildings, Sniffen Court, The Morgan Library & Museum, Gotham Hall, and the Javits Center.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 37th Street runs from the FDR Drive to Eleventh Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It runs on the north side of the Queens–Midtown Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit and over the Lincoln Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Notable locations on 37th Street are the Corinthian, the Morgan Library & Museum, Gotham Hall, and the Javits Center.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 38th Street runs from FDR Drive to Eleventh Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It runs on the south side of the Lincoln Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Notable locations on 38th Street are The Corinthian, The Town House Hotel, 425 Fifth Avenue, and the Javits Center.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 39th Street runs from First Avenue to Eleventh Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It runs over the Lincoln Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] A notable location on 39th Street is the Astro's Dog Run.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] A portion of West 46th Street between Eighth and Ninth Avenues is nicknamed **Restaurant Row**, after the number of restaurants located along its length.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Mayor John Lindsay had designated the street as Restaurant Row in 1973, honoring 16 restaurants on the block.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The Mount Vernon Hotel Museum, one of only eight surviving pre-1800 buildings in Manhattan, is located at 421 East 61st Street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The Pierre, a luxury hotel opened in 1930, is at 2 East 61st Street, at the intersection with Fifth Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The Gateway School, an independent school for children aged 5 to 14 with learning disabilities, is located at 211 West 61st Street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The Consulate-General of Russia in New York City was opened at 7–9 East 61st Street in 1933 and closed in 1948.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] East 77th and 78th streets run normally west of York Avenue, but east of York Avenue, 77th runs east, and 78th runs west, to accommodate the Pavilion at 500 East 77th.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The FDR Drive has an exit at 78th and an entrance at 79th.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] At the corner of 77th and York, on which sits PS 158, pedestrians cross 77th on red and wait on the green on the east side of York.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] As with all of Manhattan's numbered streets from 60th to 109th Street, 80th Street is divided by Central Park into eastern and western sections.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Traffic on 80th Street, on both sides of the park, runs west to east.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] West 80th Street begins at Riverside Drive on the Upper West Side, then passes West End Avenue, Broadway, and Amsterdam Avenue, then stops at Columbus Avenue when it reaches the grounds on the American Museum of Natural History.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Significant buildings on West 80th Street include those in the Riverside Drive–West 80th–81st Street Historic District, on both sides of the street's block between Riverside Drive and West End Avenue, such as the "Gothicesque" row houses at 307–317 West 80th Street designed by Charles H.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Israels, and those at 319–323 West 80th Street designed by Clarence F.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] True also designed the "vaguely Georgian" 328 West 80th Street on the same block, which also contains George F.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Pelham II's 411 West End Avenue, an Art Deco apartment building.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] East 80th Street begins at Fifth Avenue on the Upper East Side and continues past Madison, Park, Lexington, and Third, where it enters the section of the Upper East Side called Yorkville.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It then continues past Second, First, York and East End Avenues before dead-ending at the FDR Drive.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Significant buildings on East 80th Street include the American Irish Historical Society at 991 Fifth Avenue; the houses of Franklyn and Edna Woolworth and her two sisters at 2, 4, and 6 East 80th Street, built by F.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Gilbert; the postmodern 45 East 80th Street at Madison Avenue, designed by Liebman Liebman & Associates; the raw concrete 1967 Manhattan Church of Christ by Eggers & Higgins; 52 East 80th Street between Madison and Park, built in the 1890s.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Schmidt; and the same designer's Vincent and Helen Astor House at #130, built in 1927–28 and now the Junior League of the City of New York.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] At 1157 Lexington Avenue is the 1932 Unitarian Church of All Souls, designed by Robert Upjohn.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The first segment, West 90th Street begins at Riverside Drive and ends at Central Park West or West Drive, when it is open, in Central Park on the Upper West Side.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The second segment of East 90th Street begins at East Drive, at Engineers Gate of Central Park.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] When East Drive is closed, East 90th Street begins at Fifth Avenue on the Upper East Side and curves to the right at the FDR Drive becoming East End Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Our Lady of Good Counsel Church, is located on East 90th Street between Third Avenue and Second Avenue, across the street from Ruppert Towers (1601 and 1619 Third Avenue) and Ruppert Park.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Asphalt Green is a nonprofit community center dedicated to sports, fitness, and wellness located on East 90th Street between York Avenue and East End Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Above 114th Street between Amsterdam Avenue and Morningside Drive, there is a private indoor pedestrian bridge connecting two buildings on the campus of Mount Sinai Morningside.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 17 East 126th Street was the location of Art Kane's 1958 photograph of contemporary jazz musicians, now known as *A Great Day in Harlem*, which featured in the 2004 Steven Spielberg film *The Terminal*.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The 132nd Street Community Garden is located on 132nd Street between Adam Clayton Powell Jr.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] In 1997, the lot received a garden makeover; the Borough President's office funded the installation of a $100,000 water distribution system that keeps the wide variety of trees green.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The garden also holds a goldfish pond and several benches.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The spirit of the neighborhood lives in gardens like this one, planted and tended by local residents.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The Manhattanville Bus Depot (formerly known as the **132nd Street Bus Depot**) is located on West 132nd and 133rd Street between Broadway and Riverside Drive in the Manhattanville neighborhood.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 155th Street starts on the West Side at Riverside Drive, crossing Broadway, Amsterdam Avenue and St.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Nicholas Place, the terrain drops off steeply, and 155th Street is carried on a 1,600-foot (490 m) long viaduct, a City Landmark constructed in 1893, that slopes down towards the Harlem River, continuing onto the Macombs Dam Bridge, crossing over (but not intersecting with) the Harlem River Drive.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] A separate, unconnected section of 155th Street runs under the viaduct, connecting Bradhurst Avenue and the Harlem River Drive.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The New York City Subway serves 155th Street on the IND Eighth Avenue and Concourse Lines.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] West of Fort Washington Avenue, 181st Street is largely residential, bordering Hudson Heights and having a few shops to serve the local residents.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] East of Fort Washington Avenue, the street becomes increasingly commercial, becoming dominated entirely by retail stores where the street reaches Broadway and continues as such until reaching the Harlem River.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It is the area's major shopping district.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 181st Street is served by two New York City Subway lines; there is a 181st Street station at Fort Washington Avenue on the IND Eighth Avenue Line (A train) and a 181st Street station at St.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Nicholas Avenue on the IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line (1 train).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The stations are about 500 metres (550 yd) from each other and are not connected.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The George Washington Bridge Bus Terminal is a couple of blocks south on Fort Washington Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 181st Street is also the last south/west exit in New York on the Trans-Manhattan Expressway (I-95), just before crossing the George Washington Bridge to New Jersey.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 187th Street intersects with, from east to west, Laurel Hill Terrace, Amsterdam Avenue, Audubon Avenue, St.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Nicholas Avenue, Wadsworth Avenue, Broadway, Bennett Avenue, Overlook Terrace, Fort Washington Avenue, Pinehurst Avenue, Cabrini Boulevard and Chittenden Avenue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The many institutions on 187th Street include Mount Sinai Jewish Center, the Dombrov Shtiebel, and the uptown campus of Yeshiva University.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The local public elementary and middle school P.S./M.S.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 187 is located on Cabrini Boulevard, just north of 187th Street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The Dyckman Street station was formerly called "Dyckman Street–200th Street", but there has never been a street in Manhattan with that number.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] A 196th street does exist, between Broadway and Ellwood Street.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] It is the only street between what would be 193rd and 201st to have numbered signage.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The University Heights Bridge, a swing bridge across the Harlem River, connects the street with Fordham Road in the Bronx.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] While 208th Street exists as a small driveway and parking lot located just south of the 207th Street Yard, Manhattan has no streets numbered 209th or 210th.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Manhattan has no streets numbered 221st, 222nd, 223rd, or 224th, as their theoretical location is taken up by the Spuyten Duyvil Creek.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] Despite having streets numbered 225th, 227th and 228th in the Marble Hill neighborhood, Manhattan has no street numbered 226th.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] 228th Street, located in the Marble Hill neighborhood, is the highest numbered street in Manhattan.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/22nd-street-manhattan] The street numbers continue in The Bronx.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The **Affordable Care Act** (**ACA**), formally the **Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act** (**PPACA**) and informally known as **Obamacare**, is a landmark U.S. federal statute enacted by the 111th United States Congress and signed into law by President Barack Obama on March 23, 2010.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Together with amendments made to it by the Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010, it represents the U.S. healthcare system's most significant regulatory overhaul and expansion of coverage since the enactment of Medicare and Medicaid in 1965.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The ACA's major provisions came into force in 2014.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] By 2016, the uninsured share of the population had roughly halved, with estimates ranging from 20 to 24 million additional people covered.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The law also enacted delivery system reforms intended to constrain healthcare costs and improve quality.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] After it came into effect, increases in overall healthcare spending slowed, including premiums for employer-based insurance plans.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The increased coverage was due, roughly equally, to an expansion of Medicaid eligibility and changes to individual insurance markets.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Both received new spending, funded by a combination of new taxes and cuts to Medicare provider rates and Medicare Advantage.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Several Congressional Budget Office (CBO) reports stated that overall these provisions reduced the budget deficit, that repealing ACA would increase the deficit, and that the law reduced income inequality.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The act largely retained the existing structure of Medicare, Medicaid, and the employer market, but individual markets were radically overhauled.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Insurers were made to accept all applicants without charging based on pre-existing conditions or demographic status (except age).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] To combat the resultant adverse selection, the act mandated that individuals buy insurance (or pay a monetary penalty) and that insurers cover a list of "essential health benefits".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Young people were allowed to stay on their parents' insurance plans until they were 26 years old.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Before and after its enactment the ACA faced strong political opposition, calls for repeal, and legal challenges.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Supreme Court ruled that Congress cannot use the Commerce Clause to compel individuals to buy health insurance but upheld the individual mandate by recharacterizing the penalty as a tax.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The Court also held that states could opt out of the ACA's Medicaid expansion without losing existing federal Medicaid funding, while otherwise upholding the law.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] This led Republican-controlled states to not participate in Medicaid expansion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Polls initially found that 43% of Americans wanted to see the law repealed or scaled back and 49% wanted to see it expanded or enacted as is.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 set the individual mandate penalty at $0 starting in 2019.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] ACA amended the Public Health Service Act of 1944 and inserted new provisions on affordable care into Title 42 of the United States Code.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The individual insurance market was radically overhauled, and many of the law's regulations applied specifically to this market, while the structure of Medicare, Medicaid, and the employer market were largely retained.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Some regulations applied to the employer market, and the law also made delivery system changes that affected most of the health care system.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] All new individual major medical health insurance policies sold to individuals and families faced new requirements.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The requirements took effect on January 1, 2014.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The individual mandate required everyone to have insurance or pay a penalty.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The mandate and limits on open enrollment were designed to avoid the insurance death spiral, minimize the free rider problem and prevent the healthcare system from succumbing to adverse selection.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The mandate was intended to increase the size and diversity of the insured population, including more young and healthy participants to broaden the risk pool, spreading costs.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017, set to $0 the penalty for not complying with the individual mandate, starting in 2019.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] ACA mandated that health insurance exchanges be provided for each state.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The exchanges are regulated, largely online marketplaces, administered by either federal or state governments, where individuals, families and small businesses can purchase private insurance plans.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Exchanges first offered insurance for 2014.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Some exchanges also provide access to Medicaid.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] States that set up their own exchanges have some discretion on standards and prices.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] For example, states approve plans for sale, and thereby influence (through negotiations) prices.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] They can impose additional coverage requirements—such as abortion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Alternatively, states can make the federal government responsible for operating their exchanges.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Households below the federal poverty level are not eligible to receive these subsidies.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Lawful Residents and some other legally present immigrants whose household income is below 100% FPL and are not otherwise eligible for Medicaid are eligible for subsidies if they meet all other eligibility requirements.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Married people must file taxes jointly to receive subsidies.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Enrollees must have U.S. citizenship or proof of legal residency to obtain a subsidy.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The subsidies for an ACA plan purchased on an exchange stop at 400% of the federal poverty level (FPL).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] According to the Kaiser Foundation, this results in a sharp "discontinuity of treatment" at 400% FPL, which is sometimes called the "subsidy cliff".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] After-subsidy premiums for the second lowest cost silver plan (SCLSP) just below the cliff are 9.86% of income in 2019.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Subsidies are provided as an advanceable, refundable tax credit.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The amount of subsidy is sufficient to reduce the premium for the second-lowest-cost silver plan (SCLSP) on an exchange to a sliding-scale percentage of income.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The percentage is based on the percent of federal poverty level (FPL) for the household, and varies slightly from year to year.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The subsidy can be used for any plan available on the exchange, but not catastrophic plans.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The subsidy may not exceed the premium for the purchased plan.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Small businesses are eligible for a tax credit provided they enroll in the SHOP Marketplace.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] As written, ACA mandated that insurers reduce copayments and deductibles for ACA exchange enrollees earning less than 250% of the FPL.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Medicaid recipients were not eligible for the reductions.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] So-called cost-sharing reduction (CSR) subsidies were to be paid to insurance companies to fund the reductions.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] During 2017, approximately $7 billion in CSR subsidies were to be paid, versus $34 billion for premium tax credits.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The latter was defined as mandatory spending that does not require an annual Congressional appropriation.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] CSR payments were not explicitly defined as mandatory.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] This led to litigation and disruption later.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The risk-corridor program was a temporary risk management device.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] It was intended to encourage reluctant insurers into ACA insurance market from 2014 to 2016.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] For those years the Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) would cover some of the losses for insurers whose plans performed worse than they expected.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Loss-making insurers would receive payments paid for in part by profit-making insurers.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Similar risk corridors had been established for the Medicare prescription drug benefit.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] While many insurers initially offered exchange plans, the program did not pay for itself as planned, losing up to $8.3 billion for 2014 and 2015.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Authorization had to be given so DHHS could pay insurers from "general government revenues".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] However, the Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2014 stated that no funds "could be used for risk-corridor payments". leaving the government in a potential breach of contract with insurers who offered qualified health plans.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Several insurers sued the government at the United States Court of Federal Claims to recover the funds believed owed to them under the Risk Corridors program.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] While several were summarily closed, in the case of *Moda Health v the United States*, Moda Health won a $214-million judgment in February 2017.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Wheeler stated, "the Government made a promise in the risk corridors program that it has yet to fulfill.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The Supreme Court reversed this ruling in the consolidated case, *Maine Community Health Options v.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] United States*, reaffirming as with Judge Wheeler that the government had a responsibility to pay those funds under the ACA and the use of riders to de-obligate its from those payments was illegal.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The temporary reinsurance program is meant to stabilize premiums by reducing the incentive for insurers to raise premiums due to concerns about higher-risk enrollees.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Reinsurance was based on retrospective costs rather than prospective risk evaluations.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Reinsurance was available from 2014 through 2016.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Risk adjustment involves transferring funds from plans with lower-risk enrollees to plans with higher-risk enrollees.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] It was intended to encourage insurers to compete based on value and efficiency rather than by attracting healthier enrollees.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Of the three risk management programs, only risk adjustment was permanent.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Plans with low actuarial risk compensate plans with high actuarial risk.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] ACA revised and expanded Medicaid eligibility starting in 2014.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] All U.S. citizens and legal residents with income up to 133% of the poverty line would qualify for coverage in any state that participated in the Medicaid program.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Previously, states could set various lower thresholds for certain groups and were not required to cover adults without dependent children.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] A 5% "income disregard" made the effective income eligibility limit for Medicaid 138% of the poverty level.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] However, the Supreme Court ruled in *NFIB v.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Sebelius* that this provision of ACA was coercive, and that states could choose to continue at pre-ACA eligibility levels.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Income from self-employment and wages of single individuals in excess of $200,000 annually are subjected to an additional tax of 0.9%.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The threshold amount is $250,000 for a married couple filing jointly (threshold applies to their total compensation), or $125,000 for a married person filing separately.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] In ACA's companion legislation, the Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010, an additional tax of 3.8% was applied to unearned income, specifically the lesser of net investment income and the amount by which adjusted gross income exceeds the above income limits.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] ACA included an excise tax of 40% ("Cadillac tax") on total employer premium spending in excess of specified dollar amounts (initially $10,200 for single coverage and $27,500 for family coverage) indexed to inflation.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] This tax was originally scheduled to take effect in 2018, but was delayed until 2020 by the Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2016 and again to 2022.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The excise tax on high-cost health plans was completely repealed as part of H.R.1865 - Further Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2020.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Excise taxes totaling $3 billion were levied on importers and manufacturers of prescription drugs.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] An excise tax of 2.3% on medical devices and a 10% excise tax on indoor tanning services were applied as well.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The State Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP) enrollment process was simplified.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Beginning September 23, 2010, dependents were permitted to remain on their parents' insurance plan until their 26th birthday, including dependents who no longer lived with their parents, are not a dependent on a parent's tax return, are no longer a student, or are married.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Businesses that employ fifty or more people but do not offer health insurance to their full-time employees are assessed additional tax if the government has subsidized a full-time employee's healthcare through tax deductions or other means.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] This is commonly known as the employer mandate.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] This provision was included to encourage employers to continue providing insurance once the exchanges began operating.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The act includes delivery system reforms intended to constrain costs and improve quality.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] These include Medicare payment changes to discourage hospital-acquired conditions and readmissions, bundled payment initiatives, the Center for Medicare and Medicaid Innovation, the Independent Payment Advisory Board, and accountable care organizations.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Health care cost/quality initiatives included incentives to reduce hospital infections, adopt electronic medical records, and to coordinate care and prioritize quality over quantity.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Medicare switched from fee-for-service to bundled payments.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] A single payment was to be paid to a hospital and a physician group for a defined episode of care (such as a hip replacement) rather than separate payments to individual service providers.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The Medicare Shared Savings Program (MSSP) was established by section 3022 of the Affordable Care Act.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] It is the program by which an accountable care organization interacts with the federal government, and by which accountable care organizations can be created.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The Act allowed the creation of accountable care organizations (ACOs), which are groups of doctors, hospitals and other providers that commit to give coordinated care to Medicare patients.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] ACOs were allowed to continue using fee-for-service billing.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] They receive bonus payments from the government for minimizing costs while achieving quality benchmarks that emphasize prevention and mitigation of chronic disease.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Missing cost or quality benchmarks subjected them to penalties.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Unlike health maintenance organizations, ACO patients are not required to obtain all care from the ACO.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Also, unlike HMOs, ACOs must achieve quality-of-care goals.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Medicare Part D participants received a 50% discount on brand name drugs purchased after exhausting their initial coverage and before reaching the catastrophic-coverage threshold.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] By 2020, the "doughnut hole" would be completely filled.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] From 2017 onwards, states can apply for a "waiver for state innovation" which allows them to conduct experiments that meet certain criteria.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] To obtain a waiver, a state must pass legislation setting up an alternative health system that provides insurance at least as comprehensive and as affordable as ACA, covers at least as many residents and does not increase the federal deficit.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] These states can escape some of ACA's central requirements, including the individual and employer mandates and the provision of an insurance exchange.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The state would receive compensation equal to the aggregate amount of any federal subsidies and tax credits for which its residents and employers would have been eligible under ACA, if they cannot be paid under the state plan.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The Community Living Assistance Services and Supports Act (or CLASS Act) established a voluntary and public long-term care insurance option for employees, The program was abolished as impractical without ever having taken effect.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Consumer Operated and Oriented Plans (CO-OP), member-governed non-profit insurers, could start providing health care coverage, based on a 5-year federal loan.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] As of 2017, only four of the original 23 co-ops were still in operation, including Mountain Health CO-OP.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Nutrition labeling requirements officially took effect in 2010, but implementation was delayed, and they actually took effect on May 7, 2018.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] ACA followed a long series of unsuccessful attempts by one party or the other to pass major insurance reforms.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Innovations were limited to health savings accounts (2003), medical savings accounts (1996) or flexible spending accounts, which increased insurance options, but did not materially expand coverage.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Health care was a major factor in multiple elections, but until 2009, neither party had the votes to overcome the other's opposition.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The concept of an individual mandate goes back to at least 1989, when The Heritage Foundation, a conservative think-tank, proposed an individual mandate as an alternative to single-payer health care.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] It was championed for a time by conservative economists and Republican senators as a market-based approach to healthcare reform on the basis of individual responsibility and avoidance of free rider problems.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Specifically, because the 1986 Emergency Medical Treatment and Active Labor Act (EMTALA) requires any hospital participating in Medicare (nearly all do) to provide emergency care to anyone who needs it, the government often indirectly bore the cost of those without the ability to pay.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] President Bill Clinton proposed a major healthcare reform bill in 1993 that ultimately failed.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Clinton negotiated a compromise with the 105th Congress to instead enact the State Children's Health Insurance Program (SCHIP) in 1997.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The failed Clinton plan included a mandate for employers to provide health insurance to all employees through a regulated marketplace of health maintenance organizations.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Republican senators proposed an alternative that would have required individuals, but not employers, to buy insurance.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The 1993 Republican Health Equity and Access Reform Today (HEART) Act, contained a "universal coverage" requirement with a penalty for noncompliance—an individual mandate—as well as subsidies to be used in state-based 'purchasing groups'.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Advocates included prominent Republican senators such as John Chafee, Orrin Hatch, Chuck Grassley, Bob Bennett and Kit Bond.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The 1994 Republican Consumer Choice Health Security Act, initially contained an individual mandate with a penalty provision; however, author Don Nickles subsequently removed the mandate, stating, "government should not compel people to buy health insurance".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] At the time of these proposals, Republicans did not raise constitutional issues; Mark Pauly, who helped develop a proposal that included an individual mandate for George H.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Bush, remarked, "I don't remember that being raised at all.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] In 2006, an insurance expansion bill was enacted at the state level in Massachusetts.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill contained both an individual mandate and an insurance exchange.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Republican Governor Mitt Romney used a line-item veto on some provisions, and the Democratic legislature overrode some of his changes (including the mandate).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Romney's implementation of the 'Health Connector' exchange and individual mandate in Massachusetts was at first lauded by Republicans.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] During Romney's 2008 presidential campaign, Senator Jim DeMint praised Romney's ability to "take some good conservative ideas, like private health insurance, and apply them to the need to have everyone insured".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Romney said of the individual mandate: "I'm proud of what we've done.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] In 2007 Republican Senator Bob Bennett and Democratic Senator Ron Wyden introduced the Healthy Americans Act, which featured an individual mandate and state-based, regulated insurance markets called "State Health Help Agencies".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill attracted bipartisan support, but died in committee.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Many of its sponsors and co-sponsors remained in Congress during the 2008 healthcare debate.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] By 2008 many Democrats were considering this approach as the basis for healthcare reform.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Experts said the legislation that eventually emerged from Congress in 2009 and 2010 bore similarities to the 2007 bill and that it took ideas from the Massachusetts reforms.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] A driving force behind Obama's healthcare reform was Peter Orszag, Director of the Office of Management and Budget.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama called Orszag his "healthcare czar" because of his knowledge of healthcare reform.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Orszag had previously been director of the Congressional Budget Office, and under his leadership the agency had focused on using cost analysis to create an affordable and effective approach to health care reform.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Orszag claimed that healthcare reform became Obama's top agenda item because he wanted it to be his legacy.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] According to an article by Ryan Lizza in *The New Yorker*, the core of "the Obama budget is Orszag's belief [in]...a government empowered with research on the most effective medical treatments".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama bet "his presidency on Orszag's thesis of comparative effectiveness." Orszag's policies were influenced by an article in *The Annals of Internal Medicine* co-authored by Elliott S.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The article presented strong evidence based on the co-authors' research that numerous procedures, therapies and tests were being delivered with scant evidence of their medical value.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] If those procedures and tests could be eliminated, this evidence suggested, medical costs might provide the savings to give healthcare to the uninsured population.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] After reading a *New Yorker* article that used the "Dartmouth findings" to compare two counties in Texas with enormous variations in Medicare costs using hard data, Obama directed that his entire staff read it.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] More than anything else, the Dartmouth data intrigued Obama since it gave him an academic rationale for reshaping medicine.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The concept of comparing the effectiveness of healthcare options based on hard data ("comparative effectiveness" and "evidence-based medicine") was pioneered by John E.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Wennberg, founder of The Dartmouth Institute, co-founder of The Foundation for Informed Medical Decision Making and senior advisor to Health Dialog Inc., a venture that he and his researchers created to help insurers implement the Dartmouth findings.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Healthcare reform was a major topic during the 2008 Democratic presidential primaries.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] As the race narrowed, attention focused on the plans presented by the two leading candidates, Hillary Clinton and the eventual nominee, Barack Obama.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Each candidate proposed a plan to cover the approximately 45 million Americans estimated to not have health insurance at some point each year.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Clinton's proposal would have required all Americans to obtain coverage (in effect, an individual mandate), while Obama's proposal provided a subsidy without a mandate.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] During the general election, Obama said fixing healthcare would be one of his top four priorities as president.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama and his opponent, Senator John McCain, both proposed health insurance reforms, though their plans differed.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] McCain proposed tax credits for health insurance purchased in the individual market, which was estimated to reduce the number of uninsured people by about 2 million by 2018.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama proposed private and public group insurance, income-based subsidies, consumer protections, and expansions of Medicaid and SCHIP, which was estimated at the time to reduce the number of uninsured people by 33.9 million by 2018 at a higher cost.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama announced to a joint session of Congress in February 2009 his intent to work with Congress to construct a plan for healthcare reform.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] By July, a series of bills were approved by committees within the House of Representatives.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] On the Senate side, from June to September, the Senate Finance Committee held a series of 31 meetings to develop a proposal.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] This group—in particular, Democrats Max Baucus, Jeff Bingaman and Kent Conrad, along with Republicans Mike Enzi, Chuck Grassley and Olympia Snowe—met for more than 60 hours, and the principles they discussed, in conjunction with the other committees, became the foundation of a Senate bill.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] They chose this approach after concluding that filibuster-proof support in the Senate was not present for more progressive plans such as single-payer.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] By deliberately drawing on bipartisan ideas—the same basic outline was supported by former Senate Majority Leaders Howard Baker, Bob Dole, Tom Daschle and George J.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Mitchell—the bill's drafters hoped to garner the necessary votes.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] However, following the incorporation of an individual mandate into the proposal, Republicans threatened to filibuster any bill that contained it.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Senate Minority Leader Mitch McConnell, who led the Republican response, concluded Republicans should not support the bill.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Republican senators, including those who had supported earlier proposals with a similar mandate, began to describe the mandate as "unconstitutional".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] During the August 2009 summer congressional recess, many members went back to their districts and held town hall meetings on the proposals.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The nascent Tea Party movement organized protests and many conservative groups and individuals attended the meetings to oppose the proposed reforms.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Threats were made against members of Congress over the course of the debate.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] In September 2009 Obama delivered another speech to a joint session of Congress supporting the negotiations.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] On November 7, the House of Representatives passed the Affordable Health Care for America Act on a 220–215 vote and forwarded it to the Senate for passage.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The Senate began work on its own proposals while the House was still working.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The United States Constitution requires all revenue-related bills to originate in the House.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] To formally comply with this requirement, the Senate repurposed H.R.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] 3590, a bill regarding housing tax changes for service members.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] It had been passed by the House as a revenue-related modification to the Internal Revenue Code.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill became the Senate's vehicle for its healthcare reform proposal, discarding the bill's original content.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill ultimately incorporated elements of proposals that were reported favorably by the Senate Health and Finance committees.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] With the Republican Senate minority vowing to filibuster, 60 votes would be necessary to pass the Senate.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] At the start of the 111th Congress, Democrats had 58 votes.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The Minnesota Senate election was ultimately won by Democrat Al Franken, making 59.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Arlen Specter switched to the Democratic party in April 2009, giving them 60 seats, enough to end a filibuster.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Negotiations were undertaken attempting to satisfy moderate Democrats and to bring Republican senators aboard; particular attention was given to Republicans Bennett, Enzi, Grassley and Snowe.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] After the Finance Committee vote on October 15, negotiations turned to moderate Democrats.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Senate Majority Leader Harry Reid focused on satisfying centrists.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The holdouts came down to Joe Lieberman of Connecticut, an independent who caucused with Democrats, and conservative Nebraska Democrat Ben Nelson.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Lieberman's demand that the bill not include a public option was met, although supporters won various concessions, including allowing state-based public options such as Vermont's failed Green Mountain Care.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The latter half of the compromise was derisively termed the "Cornhusker Kickback" and was later removed.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] On December 23, the Senate voted 60–39 to end debate on the bill: a cloture vote to end the filibuster.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill then passed, also 60–39, on December 24, 2009, with all Democrats and two independents voting for it, and all Republicans against (except Jim Bunning, who did not vote).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill was endorsed by the American Medical Association and AARP.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] On January 19, 2010, Massachusetts Republican Scott Brown was elected to the Senate in a special election to replace the recently deceased Ted Kennedy, having campaigned on giving the Republican minority the 41st vote needed to sustain Republican filibusters.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Additionally, the symbolic importance of losing Kennedy's traditionally Democratic Massachusetts seat made many Congressional Democrats concerned about the political cost of the bill.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] With Democrats no longer able to get the 60 votes to break a filibuster in the Senate, White House Chief of Staff Rahm Emanuel argued that Democrats should scale back to a less ambitious bill, but House Speaker Nancy Pelosi pushed back, dismissing more moderate reform as "Kiddie Care".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama remained insistent on comprehensive reform.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The news that Anthem in California intended to raise premium rates for its patients by as much as 39% gave him new evidence of the need for reform.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] On February 22, he laid out a "Senate-leaning" proposal to consolidate the bills.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] He held a meeting with both parties' leaders on February 25.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The Democrats decided the House would pass the Senate's bill, to avoid another Senate vote.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] House Democrats had expected to be able to negotiate changes in a House–Senate conference before passing a final bill.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Since any bill that emerged from conference that differed from the Senate bill would have to pass the Senate over another Republican filibuster, most House Democrats agreed to pass the Senate bill on condition that it be amended by a subsequent bill.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] They drafted the Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act, which could be passed by the reconciliation process.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Per the Congressional Budget Act of 1974, reconciliation cannot be subject to a filibuster.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] But reconciliation is limited to budget changes, which is why the procedure was not used to pass ACA in the first place; the bill had inherently non-budgetary regulations.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Although the already-passed Senate bill could not have been passed by reconciliation, most of House Democrats' demands were budgetary: "these changes—higher subsidy levels, different kinds of taxes to pay for them, nixing the Nebraska Medicaid deal—mainly involve taxes and spending.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The remaining obstacle was a pivotal group of pro-life Democrats led by Bart Stupak who were initially reluctant to support the bill.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The group found the possibility of federal funding for abortion significant enough to warrant opposition.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The Senate bill had not included language that satisfied their concerns, but they could not address abortion in the reconciliation bill as it would be non-budgetary.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Instead, Obama issued Executive Order 13535, reaffirming the principles in the Hyde Amendment to continue banning the use of federal funds for abortion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] This won the support of Stupak and members of his group and assured the bill's passage.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The House passed the Senate bill with a 219–212 vote on March 21, 2010, with 34 Democrats and all 178 Republicans voting against it.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] It passed the second bill, by 220–211, the same day (with the Senate passing this bill via reconciliation by 56-43 a few days later).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The day after the passage of ACA, March 22, Republicans introduced legislation to repeal it.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama signed ACA into law on March 23, 2010.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] Since passage, Republicans have voted to repeal all or parts of the Affordable Care Act more than sixty times.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 eliminated the fine for violating the individual mandate, starting in 2019.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] (The requirement itself is still in effect.) In 2019 Congress repealed the so-called "Cadillac" tax on health insurance benefits, an excise tax on medical devices, and the Health Insurance Tax.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] The American Rescue Plan Act of 2021, enacted during the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States, expanded subsidies for marketplace health plans.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p01] A continuation of these subsidies was introduced as part of the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The law caused a significant reduction in the number and percentage of people without health insurance.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The CDC reported that the percentage of people without health insurance fell from 16.0% in 2010 to 8.9% from January to June 2016.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The uninsured rate dropped in every congressional district in the U.S. from 2013 to 2015.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The Congressional Budget Office reported in March 2016 that approximately 12 million people were covered by the exchanges (10 million of whom received subsidies) and 11 million added to Medicaid.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Another million were covered by ACA's "Basic Health Program", for a total of 24 million.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] CBO estimated that ACA would reduce the net number of uninsured by 22 million in 2016, using a slightly different computation for the above figures totaling ACA coverage of 26 million, less 4 million for reductions in "employment-based coverage" and "non-group and other coverage".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) estimated that 20.0 million adults (aged 18–64) gained healthcare coverage via ACA as of February 2016; similarly, the Urban Institute found in 2016 that 19.2 million non-elderly Americans gained health insurance coverage from 2010 to 2015.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] In 2016, CBO estimated the uninsured at approximately 27 million people, or around 10% of the population or 7–8% excluding undocumented immigrants.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] States that expanded Medicaid had a 7.3% uninsured rate on average in the first quarter of 2016, while those that did not had a 14.1% uninsured rate, among adults aged 18–64.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] As of December 2016 32 states (including Washington DC) had adopted the Medicaid extension.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2017 study found that the ACA reduced socioeconomic disparities in health care access.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The Affordable Care Act reduced the percent of Americans between 18 and 64 who were uninsured from 22.3 percent in 2010 to 12.4 percent in 2016.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] About 21 million more people have coverage ten years after the enactment of the ACA.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Ten years after its enactment studies showed that the ACA also had a positive effect on health and caused a reduction in mortality.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Excise taxes from the Affordable Care Act raised $16.3 billion in fiscal year 2015. $11.3 billion came from an excise tax placed directly on health insurers based on their market share.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Annual excise taxes totaling $3 billion were levied on importers and manufacturers of prescription drugs.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The Individual mandate tax was $695 per individual or $2,085 per family at a minimum, reaching as high as 2.5% of household income (whichever was higher).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The tax was set to $0 beginning in 2019.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] In the fiscal year 2018, the individual and employer mandates yielded $4 billion each.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Excise taxes on insurers and drug makers added $18 billion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Income tax surcharges produced 437 billion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] ACA reduced income inequality measured after taxes, due to the income tax surcharges and subsidies.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] CBO estimated that subsidies paid under the law in 2016 averaged $4,240 per person for 10 million individuals receiving them, roughly $42 billion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The tax subsidy for the employer market, was approximately $1,700 per person in 2016, or $266 billion total.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] As of August 2016, 15 states operated their own health insurance marketplace.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Other states either used the federal exchange, or operated in partnership with or supported by the federal government.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] By 2019, 12 states and Washington DC operated their own exchanges.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] As of December 2019, 37 states (including Washington DC) had adopted the Medicaid extension.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Those states that expanded Medicaid had a 7.3% uninsured rate on average in the first quarter of 2016, while the others had a 14.1% uninsured rate, among adults aged 18 to 64.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Following the Supreme Court ruling in 2012, which held that states would not lose Medicaid funding if they did not expand Medicaid under ACA, several states rejected the option.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Over half the national uninsured population lived in those states.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) estimated that the cost of expansion was $6,366 per person for 2015, about 49 percent above previous estimates.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] An estimated 9 to 10 million people had gained Medicaid coverage, mostly low-income adults.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The Kaiser Family Foundation estimated in October 2015 that 3.1 million additional people were not covered because of states that rejected the Medicaid expansion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] In many states income thresholds were significantly below 133% of the poverty line.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Many states did not make Medicaid available to childless adults at any income level.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Because subsidies on exchange insurance plans were not available to those below the poverty line, such individuals had no new options.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Absent children, non-disabled adults were not eligible for Medicaid there.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Studies of the impact of Medicaid expansion rejections calculated that up to 6.4 million people would have too much income for Medicaid but not qualify for exchange subsidies.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Several states argued that they could not afford the 10% contribution in 2020.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2016 study found that residents of Kentucky and Arkansas, which both expanded Medicaid, were more likely to receive health care services and less likely to incur emergency room costs or have trouble paying their medical bills.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Residents of Texas, which did not accept the Medicaid expansion, did not see a similar improvement during the same period.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Kentucky opted for increased managed care, while Arkansas subsidized private insurance.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Later Arkansas and Kentucky governors proposed reducing or modifying their programs.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] From 2013 to 2015, the uninsured rate dropped from 42% to 14% in Arkansas and from 40% to 9% in Kentucky, compared with 39% to 32% in Texas.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2016 DHHS study found that states that expanded Medicaid had lower premiums on exchange policies, because they had fewer low-income enrollees, whose health on average is worse than that of those with higher income.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] In September 2019, the Census Bureau reported that states that expanded Medicaid under the ACA had considerably lower uninsured rates than states that did not.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] For example, for adults between 100% and 399% of poverty level, the uninsured rate in 2018 was 12.7% in expansion states and 21.2% in non-expansion states.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Of the 14 states with uninsured rates of 10% or greater, 11 had not expanded Medicaid.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The drop in uninsured rates due to expanded Medicaid has broadened access to care among low-income adults, with post-ACA studies indicating an improvement in affordability, access to doctors, and usual sources of care.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Importantly, issues with cost-related unmet medical needs, skipped medications, paying medical bills, and annual out-of-pocket spending have been significantly reduced among low-income adults in Medicaid expansion states compared to non-expansion states.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] As well, expanded Medicaid has led to a 6.6% increase in physician visits by low-income adults, as well as increased usage of preventative care such as dental visits and cancer screenings among childless, low-income adults.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Improved health care coverage due to Medicaid expansion has been found in a variety of patient populations, such as adults with mental and substance use disorders, trauma patients, cancer patients, and people living with HIV.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Use of mental health treatment increased by 2.1 percentage points, from 43% to 45.1%.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Among trauma patients nationwide, the uninsured rate has decreased by approximately 50%.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Adult trauma patients in expansion states experienced a 13.7 percentage point reduction in uninsured rates compared to adult trauma patients in non-expansion states, and an accompanying 7.4 percentage point increase in discharge to rehabilitation.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Following Medicaid expansion and dependent coverage expansion, young adults hospitalized for acute traumatic injury in Maryland experienced a 60% increase in rehabilitation, 25% reduction in mortality, and a 29.8% reduction in failure-to-rescue.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The study found that a cancer diagnosis in 2014 was associated with a 1.9 percentage-point absolute and 33.5% relative decrease in uninsured rates compared to a diagnosis made between 2010 and 2013.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Another study, using Surveillance, Epidemiology, and End Results (SEER) Program data from 2010 to 2014, found that Medicaid expansion was associated with a 6.4% net increase in early stage (in situ, local, or regional) diagnoses of all cancers combined.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Expanded Medicaid coverage of PLWH has been positively associated with health outcomes such as viral suppression, retention of care, hospitalization rates, and morbidity at the time of hospitalization.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] An analysis of Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS) survey data found a 2.8% annual increase in viral suppression rates among all PLWH from 2010 to 2015 due to Medicaid expansion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] As an early adopter of Medicaid expansion, Massachusetts found a 65% rate of viral suppression among all PLWH and an 85% rate among those retained in healthcare in 2014, both substantially higher than the national average.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] An analysis of hospital discharge data from 2012 to 2014 in four Medicaid expansion states and two non-expansion states revealed hospitalizations of uninsured PLWH fell from 13.7% to 5.5% in the four expansion states and rose from 14.5% to 15.7% in the two non-expansion states.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Importantly, uninsured PLWH were 40% more likely to die in the hospital than insured PLWH.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Other notable health outcomes associated with Medicaid expansion include improved glucose monitoring rates for patients with diabetes, better hypertension control, and reduced rates of major post-operative morbidity.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A July 2019 study by the National Bureau of Economic Research (NBER) indicated that states enacting Medicaid expansion exhibited statistically significant reductions in mortality rates.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] From that study, states that took Medicaid expansion "saved the lives of at least 19,200 adults aged 55 to 64 over the four-year period from 2014 to 2017." Further, 15,600 older adults died prematurely in the states that did not enact Medicaid expansion in those years according to the NBER research.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Due to many states' failure to expand, many Democrats co-sponsored the proposed 2021 Cover Now Act that would allow county and municipal governments to fund Medicaid expansion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Despite the significant increase in access to insurance coverage and healthcare services across the board, the ACA's Medicaid expansion has not fully addressed problems of economic equity.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Critics argue that Medicaid expansion has not reduced cost-sharing by a significant margin, as the amount households paid out of pocket for healthcare over the past ten years (in the form of deductibles, co-payments, etc.) rose by 77%.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Additionally, 30% of providers deny Medicaid patients, which affects the accessibility of quality care.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] This increase in denial may be in part because providers receive 62 cents from Medicaid for every dollar received from private insurers.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Studies on insurance rates show that economic inequality still persists: a significantly higher proportion of those with income greater than 100% but less than 200% of the federal poverty level were uninsured from 2010 to 2015 than of those with income greater than 200% of the federal poverty level.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] This is exacerbated by the 2012 Supreme Court decision allowing states to opt out of Medicaid, since many of the states that have opted out have more vulnerable populations, with large numbers of minorities or low-income people.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Medicaid patients have also reported receiving "second-class" treatment compared to privately insured patients, with longer wait times and lower quality of care.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] National health care expenditures rose faster than national income both before (2009–2013: 3.73%) and after (2014–2018: 4.82%) ACA's major provisions took effect.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Premium prices rose considerably before and after.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] For example, a study published in 2016 found that the average requested 2017 premium increase among 40-year-old non-smokers was about 9 percent, although Blue Cross Blue Shield proposed increases of 40 percent in Alabama and 60 percent in Texas.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] However, some or all these costs were offset by tax credits.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] For example, the Kaiser Family Foundation reported that for the second-lowest cost "Silver plan", a 40-year old non-smoker making $30,000 per year would pay effectively the same amount in 2017 as they did in 2016 (about $208/month) after the tax credit, despite a large increase in the list price.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] In other words, the subsidies increased along with the premium price, fully offsetting the increases for subsidy-eligible enrollees.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Premium cost increases in the employer market moderated after 2009.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] For example, healthcare premiums for those covered by employers rose by 69% from 2000 to 2005, but only 27% from 2010 to 2015, with only a 3% increase from 2015 to 2016.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] From 2008 to 2010 (before passage of ACA) health insurance premiums rose by an average of 10% per year.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Several studies found that the 2008 financial crisis and accompanying Great Recession could not account for the entirety of the slowdown and that structural changes likely shared at least partial credit.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2013 study estimated that changes to the health system had been responsible for about a quarter of the recent reduction in inflation.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Paul Krawzak claimed that even if cost controls succeed in reducing the amount spent on healthcare, such efforts on their own may be insufficient to outweigh the long-term burden placed by demographic changes, particularly the growth of the population on Medicare.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A contributing factor to premium cost moderation was that the insured faced higher deductibles, copayments and out-of-pocket maximums.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] In addition, many employees chose to combine a health savings account with higher deductible plans, making the net impact of ACA difficult to determine precisely.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] According to a 2014 study, ACA likely prevented an estimated 50,000 preventable patient deaths from 2010 to 2013.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Himmelstein and Woolhandler wrote in January 2017 that a rollback of ACA's Medicaid expansion alone would cause an estimated 43,956 deaths annually.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] According to the Kaiser Foundation, expanding Medicaid in the remaining states would cover up to 4.5 million persons.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2021 study found a significant decline in mortality rates in the states that opted in to the Medicaid expansion program compared with those states that did not do so.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The study reported that states decisions' not to expand Medicaid resulted in approximately 15,600 excess deaths from 2014 through 2017.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Dependent Coverage Expansion (DCE) under the ACA has had a demonstrable effect on various health metrics of young adults, a group with a historically low level of insurance coverage and utilization of care.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Studies have also found that DCE was associated with improvements in cancer prevention, detection, and treatment among young adult patients.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A study of 10,010 women aged 18–26 identified through the 2008-12 National Health Interview Survey found that the likelihood of HPV vaccination initiation and completion increased by 7.7 and 5.8 percentage points respectively when comparing before and after October 1, 2010.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A study using SEER Program data from 2007 to 2012 found a 2.7 percentage point increase in diagnosis at stage I disease for patients aged 19–25 compared with those aged 26–34 for all cancers combined.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Two 2018 *JAMA* studies found the Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program (HRRP) was associated with increased post-discharge mortality for patients hospitalized for heart failure and pneumonia.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2019 *JAMA* study found that ACA decreased emergency department and hospital use by uninsured individuals.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The HRRP was also shown to disproportionately penalize safety-net hospitals that predominately serve low-income patients.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The study concluded that the letters, sent to 3.9 million people, may have saved 700 lives.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2020 *JAMA* study found that Medicare expansion under the ACA was associated with reduced incidence of advanced-stage breast cancer, indicating that Medicaid accessibility led to early detection of breast cancer and higher survival rates.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Recent studies have also attributed to Medicaid expansion an increase in use of smoking cessation medications, cervical cancer screening, and colonoscopy, as well as an increase in the percentage of early-stage diagnosis of all cancers and the rate of cancer surgery for low-income patients.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Transition-of-care interventions and Alternative Payment Models under the ACA have also shown promise in improving health outcomes.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Post-discharge provider appointment and telephone follow-up interventions have been shown to reduce 30-day readmission rates among general medical-surgical inpatients.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Reductions in 60, 90, and 180 post-discharge day readmission rates due to transition-of-care interventions have also been demonstrated, and a reduction in 30-day mortality has been suggested.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The patient-centered medical home (PCMH) payment and care model, a team-based approach to population health management that risk-stratifies patients and provides focused care management and outreach to high-risk patients, has been shown to improve diabetes outcomes.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The ACA overall has improved coverage and care of diabetes, with a significant portion of the 3.5 million uninsured US adults aged 18–64 with diabetes in 2009-10 likely gaining coverage and benefits such as closure of the Medicaid Part D coverage gap for insulin.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The law placed relatively little burden on households in the top quintile (top 20%) outside of the top 1%.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO reported in multiple studies that ACA would reduce the deficit, and repealing it would increase the deficit, primarily because of the elimination of Medicare reimbursement cuts.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The 2011 comprehensive CBO estimate projected a net deficit reduction of more than $200 billion during the 2012–2021 period: it calculated the law would result in $604 billion in total outlays offset by $813 billion in total receipts, resulting in a $210 billion net deficit reduction.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO separately predicted that while most of the spending provisions do not begin until 2014, revenue would exceed spending in those subsequent years.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] This estimate was made prior to the Supreme Court's ruling that enabled states to opt out of the Medicaid expansion, thereby forgoing the related federal funding.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO and JCT subsequently updated the budget projection, estimating the impact of the ruling would reduce the cost estimate of the insurance coverage provisions by $84 billion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO in June 2015 forecast that repeal of ACA would increase the deficit between $137 billion and $353 billion over the 2016–2025 period, depending on the impact of macroeconomic feedback effects.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO also forecast that repeal of ACA would likely cause an increase in GDP by an average of 0.7% in the period from 2021 to 2025, mainly by boosting the supply of labor.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Although the CBO generally does not provide cost estimates beyond the 10-year budget projection period because of the degree of uncertainty involved in the projection, it decided to do so in this case at the request of lawmakers, and estimated a second decade deficit reduction of $1.2 trillion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] CBO predicted deficit reduction around a broad range of one-half percent of GDP over the 2020s while cautioning that "a wide range of changes could occur".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] In 2017 CBO estimated that repealing the individual mandate alone would reduce the 10-year deficit by $338 billion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO cost estimates were criticized because they excluded the effects of potential legislation that would increase Medicare payments by more than $200 billion from 2010 to 2019.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] However, the so-called "doc fix" is a separate issue that would have existed with or without ACA.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The Center on Budget and Policy Priorities objected that Congress had a good record of implementing Medicare savings.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] According to their study, Congress followed through on the implementation of the vast majority of provisions enacted in the past 20 years to produce Medicare savings, although not the doc fix.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The doc fix became obsolete in 2015 when the savings provision was eliminated, permanently removing that spending restraint.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Scheiber and Cohn rejected critical assessments of the law's deficit impact, arguing that predictions were biased towards underestimating deficit reduction.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] In 2010 David Walker said the CBO estimates were not likely to be accurate, because they were based on the assumption that the law would not change.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The employer mandate applies to employers of more than fifty where health insurance is provided only to the full-time workers.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Critics claimed it created a perverse incentive to hire part-timers instead.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] However, between March 2010 and 2014, the number of part-time jobs declined by 230,000 while the number of full-time jobs increased by two million.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] In the public sector full-time jobs turned into part-time jobs much more than in the private sector.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2016 study found only limited evidence that ACA had increased part-time employment.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Several businesses and the state of Virginia added a 29-hour-a-week cap for their part-time employees, to reflect the 30-hour-or-more definition for full-time worker.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] As of 2013, few companies had shifted their workforce towards more part-time hours (4% in a survey from the Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Trends in working hours and the recovery from the Great Recession correlate with the shift from part-time to full-time work.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Other confounding impacts include that health insurance helps attract and retain employees, increases productivity and reduces absenteeism; and lowers corresponding training and administration costs from a smaller, more stable workforce.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Relatively few firms employ over 50 employees and more than 90% of them already offered insurance.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Most policy analysts (both right and left) were critical of the employer mandate provision.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The provision generated vocal opposition from business interests and some unions who were not granted exemptions.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] From the start of 2010 to November 2014, 43 hospitals in rural areas closed.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Critics claimed the new law had caused these closures.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Many rural hospitals were built using funds from the 1946 Hill–Burton Act.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Some of these hospitals reopened as other medical facilities, but only a small number operated emergency rooms (ER) or urgent care centers.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Between January 2010 and 2015, a quarter of ER doctors said they had seen a major surge in patients, while nearly half had seen a smaller increase.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Seven in ten ER doctors claimed they lacked the resources to deal with large increases in the number of patients.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The biggest factor in the increased number of ER patients was insufficient primary care providers to handle the larger number of insured.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Monuteaux at Boston Children's Hospital analyzed national emergency department visits among children aged 0 to 17 from 2009 to 2016 using the American Community Survey (ACS) and Nationwide Emergency Department Sample (NEDS).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] They found no immediate change in pediatric emergency department visit rates the year after the ACA took full effect in 2014, but the rate of change from 2014 to 2016 was significantly higher than previous rate trends, almost 10%.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Many hospitals merged and purchased physician practices, amounting to a significant consolidation of the provider industry.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] The increased market share gave them more leverage with insurers and reduced patient care options.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] In 2015 the progressive Center for Economic and Policy Research found no evidence that companies were reducing worker hours to avoid ACA requirements for employees working more than 30 hours per week.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] CBO estimated that ACA would slightly reduce the size of the labor force and number of hours worked, as some would no longer be tethered to employers for their insurance.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Jonathan Cohn claimed that ACA's primary employment effect was to alleviate job lock and the reform's only significant employment impact was the retirement of those who were working only to stay insured.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] ACA updated a portion of the False Claims Act that the United States Supreme Court interpreted in *Graham County Soil & Water Conservation District v.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] There, the court said that a subsection giving public officials immunity to *qui tam* lawsuits for false statements in "administrative" disclosures encompassed state officials as well as federal ones.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Because of ACA, that section specifies that the immunity is limited to federal disclosures.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Public views became increasingly negative in reaction to specific plans discussed during the legislative debate over 2009 and 2010.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Some elements were more widely favored (preexisting conditions) or opposed (individual mandate).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Other polls found that people were concerned the law would cost more than projected and would not do enough to control costs.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] In a 2012 poll 44% supported the law, with 56% against.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] By 75% of Democrats, 27% of Independents and 14% of Republicans favored the law.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] By party affiliation, 19% of Republicans, 27% of Independents, and 59% of Democrats favored the mandate.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Other polls showed additional provisions receiving majority support, including the exchanges, pooling small businesses and the uninsured with other consumers and providing subsidies.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] In June 2013, a majority of the public (52–34%) indicated a desire for "Congress to implement or tinker with the law rather than repeal it".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] After the Supreme Court upheld the individual mandate, a 2012 poll held that "most Americans (56%) want to see critics of President Obama's health care law drop efforts to block it and move on to other national issues".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] As of October 2013, approximately 40% were in favor while 51% were against.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] About 29% of whites approved of the law, compared with 61% of Hispanics and 91% of African Americans.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A solid majority of seniors opposed the idea and a solid majority of those under forty were in favor.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2014 poll reported that 26% of Americans support ACA.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A later 2014 poll reported that 48.9% of respondents had an unfavorable view of ACA versus 38.3% who had a favorable view (of more than 5,500 individuals).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Another held that 8% of respondents agreed the Affordable Care Act "is working well the way it is".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] In late 2014, a Rasmussen poll reported Repeal: 30%, Leave as is: 13%, Improve: 52%.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] In 2015, a poll reported that 47% of Americans approved the health care law.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] This was the first time a major poll indicated that more respondents approved than disapproved.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A December 2016 poll reported that: a) 30% wanted to expand what the law does; b) 26% wanted to repeal the entire law; c) 19% wanted to move forward with implementing the law as it is; and d) 17% wanted to scale back what the law does, with the remainder undecided.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Separate polls from Fox News and NBC/*WSJ*, both taken during January 2017, indicated more people viewed the law favorably than did not for the first time.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] One of the reasons for the improving popularity of the law is that Democrats who had once opposed it (many still prefer "Medicare for all") shifted their positions because ACA was under threat of repeal.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] Another January 2017 poll reported that 35% of respondents believed "Obamacare" and the "Affordable Care Act" were different or did not know.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2017 study found that personal experience with public health insurance programs led to greater support for the ACA, most prominently among Republicans and low-information voters.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] By the end of 2023, a Morning Consult poll of registered voters found that 57% approved of the Affordable Care Act, while 30% disapproved of it.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p02] 85% of Democrats, 56% of independents, and 28% of Republicans supported the law.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The term "Obamacare" was originally coined by opponents as a pejorative.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] According to research by Elspeth Reeve, the expression was used in early 2007, generally by writers describing the candidate's proposal for expanding coverage for the uninsured.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The term officially emerged in March 2007 when healthcare lobbyist Jeanne Schulte Scott wrote, "We will soon see a 'Giuliani-care' and 'Obama-care' to go along with 'McCain-care', 'Edwards-care', and a totally revamped and remodeled 'Hillary-care' from the 1990s".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In May 2007, Mitt Romney introduced it to political discourse, saying, "How can we get those people insured without raising taxes and without having government take over healthcare?' And let me tell you, if we don't do it, the Democrats will.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] If the Democrats do it, it will be socialized medicine; it'll be government-managed care.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] By mid-2012, Obamacare had become the colloquial term used both by supporters and opponents.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Obama eventually endorsed the nickname, saying, "I have no problem with people saying Obama cares.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] I do care." By 2016 Obama explicitly and repeatedly referred to the ACA as "Obamacare".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] On August 7, 2009, Sarah Palin created the term "death panels" to describe groups who would decide whether sick patients were "worthy" of medical care.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] "Death panel" referred to two claims about early drafts.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] One was that under the law, seniors could be denied care due to their age and the other that the government would advise seniors to end their lives instead of receiving care.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The ostensible basis of these claims was the provision for an Independent Payment Advisory Board (IPAB).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] IPAB was given the authority to recommend cost-saving changes to Medicare by facilitating the adoption of cost-effective treatments and cost-recovering measures when statutory expenditure levels were exceeded within any given three-year period.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In fact, the Board was prohibited from recommending changes that would reduce payments before 2020, and was prohibited from recommending changes in premiums, benefits, eligibility and taxes, or other changes that would result in rationing.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In 2010, the Pew Research Center reported that 85% of Americans were familiar with the claim, and 30% believed it was true, backed by three contemporaneous polls.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The allegation was named PolitiFact's 2009 "Lie of the Year", one of FactCheck.org's "whoppers" and the most outrageous term by the American Dialect Society.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] AARP described such rumors as "rife with gross—and even cruel—distortions".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] ACA requires members of Congress and their staffs to obtain health insurance either through an exchange or some other program approved by the law (such as Medicare), instead of using the insurance offered to federal employees (the Federal Employees Health Benefits Program).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] ACA explicitly denies insurance subsidies to "unauthorized (illegal) aliens".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Opponents claimed that combining immediate coverage with no provision for preexisting conditions would lead people to wait to get insured until they got sick.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The individual mandate was designed to push people to get insured without waiting.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In the years after 2013, many insurers did leave specific marketplaces, claiming the risk pools were too small.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Five states had one insurer in 2017, 13 had two, 11 had three; the remainder had four or more.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Obama's previous unambiguous assurance that consumers could keep their own plans became a focal point for critics, who challenged his truthfulness.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Various bills were introduced in Congress to allow people to keep their plans.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] PolitiFact initially cited various estimates that only about 2% of the total insured population (4 million out of 262 million) received such notices, but readers later voted Obama's claims as the 2013 "Lie of the Year".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Opposition and efforts to repeal the legislation have drawn support from sources that include labor unions, conservative advocacy groups, Republicans, small business organizations and the Tea Party movement.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] These groups claimed the law would disrupt existing health plans, increase costs from new insurance standards, and increase the deficit.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Some opposed the idea of universal healthcare.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] President Donald Trump repeatedly promised to "repeal and replace" it.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In October 2016, Mark Dayton, the governor of Minnesota, said ACA had "many good features" but it was "no longer affordable for increasing numbers of people"; he called on the state legislature to provide emergency relief to policyholders.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Dayton later said he regretted his remarks after they were seized on by Republicans seeking to repeal the law.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Some pointed out that the previous system also had socialist aspects.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Even for-profit private health insurance companies socialize risk and redistribute wealth from people who have it (all premium payers) to those who need it (by paying for medically necessary healthcare).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The requirement to provide emergency care also forced redistribution from people who pay insurance premiums to those who choose to be uninsured, when they visit the emergency room.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Milos Forman opined that critics "falsely equate Western European-style socialism, and its government provision of social insurance and health care, with Marxist–Leninist totalitarianism".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Opponents challenged ACA's constitutionality in multiple lawsuits on multiple grounds.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The Supreme Court ruled, 5–4, that the individual mandate was constitutional when viewed as a tax, although not under the Commerce Clause.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] ACA withheld all Medicaid funding from states declining to participate in the expansion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The Court ruled that this was unconstitutionally coercive and that individual states had the right to opt out without losing preexisting Medicaid funding.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Various lawsuits addressed these concerns, including *Burwell v.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Hobby Lobby Stores, Inc.*, which looked at private corporations and their duties under the ACA.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In *Little Sisters of the Poor Saints Peter and Paul Home v.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Pennsylvania*, the Supreme Court ruled 7–2 on July 8, 2020, that employers with religious or moral objections to contraceptives can exclude such coverage from an employee's insurance plan.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Writing for the majority, Justice Clarence Thomas said, "No language in the statute itself even hints that Congress intended that contraception should or must be covered.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] It was Congress, not the [administration], that declined to expressly require contraceptive coverage in the ACA itself." Justices Roberts, Alito, Gorsuch, and Kavanaugh joined Thomas's opinion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Justice Elena Kagan filed a concurring opinion in the judgment, in which Stephen Breyer joined.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The Biden administration planned to seek a hold on O'Connor's decision.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Supreme Court ruled, 6–3, that federal subsidies for health insurance premiums could be used in the 34 states that did not set up their own insurance exchanges.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] House Republicans sued the Obama administration in 2014, alleging that cost-sharing reduction subsidy payments to insurers were unlawful because Congress had not appropriated funds to pay for them.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The argument classified the CSR subsidy as discretionary spending subject to annual appropriation.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In May 2016, a federal judge ruled for the plaintiffs, but the Obama administration appealed.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Later, President Trump ended the payments.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The House sued the administration, alleging that the money for CSRs to insurers had not been appropriated, as required for any federal government spending.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The ACA subsidy that helps customers pay premiums was not part of the suit.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Without the CSRs, the government estimated that premiums would increase by 20% to 30% for silver plans.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In 2017, the uncertainty about whether the payments would continue caused Blue Cross Blue Shield of North Carolina to try to raise premiums by 22.9% the next year, as opposed to an increase of 8.8% that it would have sought if the payments were assured.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Collyer ruled that the cost-sharing program was unconstitutional for spending money that has not been specifically provided by an act of Congress, but concluded that Congress had in fact authorized that program to be created.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The judge also found that Congress had provided authority to cover the spending for the tax credits to consumers who use them to help afford health coverage.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Collyer enjoined further cost-sharing payments, but stayed the order pending appeal to the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The case ended in a settlement before the Circuit Court.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The Department of Justice said it would no longer defend the ACA in court, but 17 states led by California stepped in to do so.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] O'Connor's decision regarding severability turned on several passages from the Congressional debate that focused on the importance of the mandate.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] While he ruled the law unconstitutional, he did not overturn the law.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The intervening states appealed the decision to the Fifth Circuit.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] These states argued that Congress's change in the tax was only reducing the amount of the tax, and that Congress had the power to write a stronger law to this end.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] O'Connor stayed his decision pending the appeal.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The Fifth Circuit heard the appeal on July 9, 2019; in the interim, the U.S.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Department of Justice joined with Republican states to argue that the ACA was unconstitutional, while the Democratic states were joined by the Democrat-controlled U.S.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] An additional question was addressed, as the Republican plaintiffs challenged the Democratic states' standing to defend the ACA.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In December 2019, the Fifth Circuit agreed the individual mandate was unconstitutional, but did not agree that the entire law should be voided.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Instead, it remanded the case to the District Court for reconsideration of that question.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The Supreme Court accepted the case in March 2020, to be heard in the 2020–2021 term, with the ruling likely falling after the 2020 elections.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Democrats pointed out that the effect of invalidating the entire law would be to remove popular provisions such as the protection for preexisting conditions, and that the Republicans had still not offered any replacement plan—important issues in the 2020 elections.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] On June 17, 2021, the Court rejected the challenge in a 7–2 decision, ruling that Texas and the other plaintiff states did not have standing to challenge the provision, leaving the full ACA intact.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In April 2024, the Biden administration issued a final rule implementing Section 1557 of the ACA, adding gender identity to Title IX's definition of discrimination based on sex.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In May 2024, 15 states led by Tennessee sued HHS in the U.S.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] District Court for the Southern District of Mississippi, arguing that the 2024 rule violated the Administrative Procedure Act and the U.S.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In October 2025, a federal judge struck down the 2024 rule to the extent that it prohibits discrimination against transgender people in education and health-care programs.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The Supreme Court ruled that promised risk corridor payments must be made even in the absence of specific appropriation of money by Congress.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Officials in Texas, Florida, Alabama, Wyoming, Arizona, Oklahoma and Missouri opposed those elements over which they had discretion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] For example, Missouri declined to expand Medicaid or establish a health insurance marketplace engaging in active non-cooperation, enacting a statute forbidding any state or local official to render any aid not specifically required by federal law.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Other Republicans discouraged efforts to advertise the law's benefits.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Some conservative political groups launched ad campaigns to discourage enrollment.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] ACA was the subject of many unsuccessful repeal efforts by Republicans in the 111th, 112th, and 113th Congresses: Representatives Steve King and Michele Bachmann introduced bills in the House to repeal the ACA the day after it was signed, as did Senator Jim DeMint in the Senate.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In 2011, after Republicans gained control of the House, one of the first votes held was on a bill titled "Repealing the Job-Killing Health Care Law Act" (H.R.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] All Republicans and three Democrats voted for repeal.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In the Senate, the bill was offered as an amendment to an unrelated bill, but was voted down.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] President Obama said he would veto the bill had it passed.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] On February 3, 2015, the House of Representatives added its 67th repeal vote to the record (239 to 186).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Strong partisan disagreement in Congress prevented adjustments to the Act's provisions.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] But at least one change, a proposed repeal of a tax on medical devices, received bipartisan support.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Some Congressional Republicans argued against improvements to the law on the grounds that they would weaken the arguments for repeal.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Republicans attempted to defund the ACA's implementation, and in October 2013 House Republicans refused to fund the federal government unless it came with an implementation delay, after Obama unilaterally deferred the employer mandate by one year, which critics claimed he had no power to do.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The House passed three versions of a bill funding the government while submitting various versions that would repeal or delay the ACA, with the last version delaying enforcement of the individual mandate.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The Democratic Senate leadership said the Senate would pass only a bill without any restrictions on ACA.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The government shutdown lasted from October 1 to October 17.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] During a midnight congressional session starting January 11, the Senate of the 115th Congress of the United States voted to approve a "budget blueprint" that would allow Republicans to repeal parts of the law "without threat of a Democratic filibuster".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The plan, which passed 51–48, was named by Senate Republicans the "Obamacare 'repeal resolution.'" Democrats opposing the resolution staged a protest during the vote.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] House Republicans announced their replacement, the American Health Care Act, on March 6.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] On March 24, the AHCA failed amid a revolt among Republican representatives.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] On May 4 the House voted to pass the AHCA by a margin of 217 to 213.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The Senate Republican leadership announced that Senate Republicans would write their own version of the bill instead of voting on the House version.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Leader McConnell named a group of 13 Republicans to draft the substitute version in private, raising bipartisan concerns about lack of transparency.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] On June 22, Republicans released the first discussion draft, which renamed it the "Better Care Reconciliation Act of 2017" (BCRA).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] On July 25, although no amendment proposal had garnered majority support, Republicans voted to advance the bill to the floor and begin formal consideration of amendments.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Senators Susan Collins and Lisa Murkowski were the only two dissenting Republicans, making the vote a 50–50 tie.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Vice President Mike Pence then cast the tie-breaking vote in the affirmative.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] A subsequent "Obamacare Repeal and Reconciliation Act" abandoned the "repeal and replace" approach in favor of a straight repeal, but that too failed, 45–55.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Finally, the "Health Care Freedom Act", nicknamed "skinny repeal" because it would have made the least change to ACA, failed by 49–51, with Collins, Murkowski, and McCain joining all Democrats and independents in voting against it.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Donald Trump, who has historically opposed the ACA, said during the 2024 United States presidential debates that he had "concepts of a plan" to modify or scrap it.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] JD Vance has said that Trump intends to allow insurance companies to discriminate against people with preexisting conditions or disability, with subsidized insurance replaced with private insurance.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Kamala Harris said during her 2024 campaign that she would "maintain and grow" the ACA.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] During the 2025 federal government shutdown, the ACA once again became a focal point of partisan disagreement.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] On November 8–9, 2025, as the shutdown reached its 39th day, President Donald Trump urged Senate Republicans to redirect federal funds used for ACA insurance subsidies toward direct cash payments to individuals, framing the proposal as a strategy to resolve the budgetary impasse.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Several Republican senators expressed openness to the idea; Democrats rejected it.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Analysts noted that the proposal lacked the bipartisan support necessary to reopen the federal government.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Contemporary reports described the dispute over the ACA's subsidy structure as one of the key issues contributing to the protracted shutdown.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Trump said he believed the law will expire once its tax credit is eliminated and not renewed.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The disagreement focused on whether to continue the enhanced premium tax credits expanded under previous legislation, including the American Rescue Plan, which lowered the portion of health insurance costs consumers pay.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Observers noted that if these subsidies expired, many individuals could face significant premium increases, potentially more than doubling for some enrollees.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] This raised concerns about decreased enrollment in the ACA marketplaces, especially among individuals who previously received little or no subsidy.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In addition to the effects on consumers, small businesses and self-employed individuals relying on ACA marketplace plans faced potential financial strain.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Reports also highlighted that certain federal health agency employees were furloughed during the shutdown, temporarily affecting the oversight and administration of health programs.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The debate over ACA funding illustrated how federal budget impasses can have immediate effects on both insurance markets and the delivery of health services.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Under both the ACA (current law) and the AHCA, the CBO reported that the health exchange marketplaces would remain stable.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] But Republican politicians took a variety of steps to undermine it, creating uncertainty that adversely impacted enrollment and insurer participation while increasing premiums.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Concern about the exchanges became another argument for reforms.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In December 2009, former DNC chairman and former Vermont governor Howard Dean called the ACA "a bigger bailout for the insurance industry than AIG" and "an insurance company's dream".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] He viewed the bill's end form as a death of the health care reform effort.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In his 2011 book *Remedy and Reaction*, Paul Starr, the former senior advisor for Bill Clinton's health care reform plan, notes that the ACA did not make health insurance a right and did not make medical care free at the point of service.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] He criticizies the ACA on the grounds that some lower-income individuals still cannot afford treatment and go without care "if health care and insurance are treated as ordinary commodities".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The ACA's critics often cite its inability to control costs and lower deductibles, the difficulty for average people to compare plans, lack of a strong public option, and inadequate regulations on or alternatives (such as co-operatives) to large corporate health care companies.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In 2010 small business tax credits took effect.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Then Pre-Existing Condition Insurance Plan (PCIP) took effect to offer insurance to those who had been denied coverage by private insurance companies because of a preexisting condition.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] By 2011, insurers had stopped marketing child-only policies in 17 states, as they sought to escape this requirement.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In *National Federation of Independent Business v.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Sebelius* the Supreme Court allowed states to opt out of the Medicaid expansion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In 2013, the Internal Revenue Service ruled that the cost of covering only the individual employee would be considered in determining whether the cost of coverage exceeded 9.5% of income.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Family plans would not be considered even if the cost was above the 9.5% income threshold.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] On July 2 Obama delayed the employer mandate until 2015.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The launch for both the state and federal exchanges was beset by management and technical failings.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] HealthCare.gov, the website that offers insurance through the exchanges operated by the federal government, crashed on opening and suffered many problems.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Operations stabilized in 2014, although not all planned features were complete.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The Government Accountability Office released a non-partisan study in 2014 that concluded the administration had not provided "effective planning or oversight practices" in developing the exchanges.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Hobby Lobby* the Supreme Court exempted closely held corporations with religious convictions from the contraception rule.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] At the beginning of the 2015, 11.7 million had signed up (ex-Medicaid).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] By the end of the year about 8.8 million consumers had stayed in the program.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] Congress repeatedly delayed the onset of the "Cadillac tax" on expensive insurance plans first until 2020 and later until 2022 and repealed it in late 2019.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] An estimated 9 to 10 million people had gained Medicaid coverage in 2016, mostly low-income adults.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The five major national insurers expected to lose money on ACA policies in 2016, in part because the enrollees were lower income, older and sicker than expected.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] More than 9.2 million people (3.0 million new customers and 6.2 million returning) enrolled on the national exchange in 2017, down some 400,000 from 2016.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] This decline was due primarily to the election of President Trump.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The eleven states that run their own exchanges signed up about 3 million more.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The IRS announced that it would not require that tax returns indicate a person has health insurance, reducing the effectiveness of the individual mandate, in response to Trump's executive order.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The CBO reported in March that the healthcare exchanges were expected to be stable.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] In May the House voted to repeal the ACA using the American Health Care Act (AHCA), but the AHCA was defeated in the Senate.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act set the individual mandate penalty at $0 starting in 2019.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The CBO estimated that the change would cause 13 million fewer people to have health insurance in 2027.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The 2017 Individual Market Stabilization Bill was proposed to fund cost-sharing reductions, provide more flexibility for state waivers, allow a new "Copper Plan" offering only catastrophic coverage, allow interstate insurance compacts, and redirect consumer fees to states for outreach.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] By 2019, 35 states and the District of Columbia had either expanded coverage via traditional Medicaid or via an alternative program.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/affordable-care-act-p03] The show aired another sketch in September 2013 with Jay Pharoah as President Obama rolling out the plan to the public, and Aaron Paul and other cast members playing ordinary Americans helping him in advocating for the legislation.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/aia-guide-to-new-york-city] The ***AIA Guide to New York City*** by Norval White, Elliot Willensky, and Fran Leadon is an extensive catalogue with descriptions, critique and photographs of significant and noteworthy architecture throughout the five boroughs of New York City.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/aia-guide-to-new-york-city] Originally published in 1967 and written by Norval White and Elliot Willensky, the fifth edition, with new co-author Fran Leadon (and minus Willensky, who died in 1990), was published in 2010.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/aia-guide-to-new-york-city] The book covers the architecture of nearly 6000 buildings in New York City.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] Sloan Foundation** is an American philanthropic nonprofit organization.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] Sloan Jr., president and chief executive officer of General Motors.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] The Sloan Foundation makes grants to support original research and broad-based education related to science, technology, and economics.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] The foundation is an independent entity and has no formal relationship with General Motors.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] As of 2024, the Sloan Foundation's assets totaled $2.2 billion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] Sloan's presidency, the foundation devoted its resources almost exclusively to education in economics and business.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] Sloan, an economist and Alfred's younger brother, served as director and vice president of the foundation.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] The Sloan Foundation also made many civic contributions to the foundation's home city of New York, including grants to Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts, Channel 13, New York Public Library, New York University, and the Fund for the City of New York.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] Starting in 2026, Stacie Bloom assumed presidency of the foundation.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] The Sloan Work and Family Researchers Network supports research and education about work-family issues.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] The foundation also funded the national workplace flexibility campaign as part of the Working Families program led by Kathleen E.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] The Sloan Research Fellowships are annual awards given to more than 126 young researchers and university faculty, to further studies in chemistry, computational and evolutionary microbiology, computer science, economics, mathematics, neuroscience, ocean sciences and physics.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] In March 2008, the foundation awarded a $3 million grant to the Wikimedia Foundation.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] It made additional grants in July 2011 and January 2017.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] The Sloan Foundation is the primary funder of the Sloan Digital Sky Survey, a major astronomical survey that began data collection in 2000.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] In 1945, the Sloan Foundation donated $4 million to launch the Sloan Kettering Cancer Institute, now the Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] In 1950, the Sloan Foundation made a gift of more than $5 million to establish a School of Industrial Management, now known as the MIT Sloan School of Management.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alfred-p-sloan-foundation] In 1955, the Sloan Foundation made a gift to establish the first two-year academic program in healthcare management in the US at Cornell University, initially called the Sloan Institute of Hospital Administration and now known as the Sloan Program in Health Administration.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Her paintings have an expressionistic use of line and color, psychological acumen, and emotional intensity.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] She pursued a career as a figurative painter during a period when abstraction was favored, and she did not begin to gain critical praise for her work until the 1960s.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Her work contradicts and challenges the traditional and objectified nude depictions of women by her male predecessors.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] This is done by depicting women through a female gaze, illustrating them as being consciously aware of the objectification by men and the demoralizing effects of the male gaze.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Alice Neel was born on January 28, 1900, in Merion Square, Pennsylvania.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Her father was George Washington Neel, an accountant for the Pennsylvania Railroad, and her mother was Alice Concross Hartley Neel.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In mid-1900 her family moved to the rural town of Colwyn, Pennsylvania.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Young Alice was the fourth of five children with three brothers and a sister.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Her siblings were named Hartley, Albert, Lillian, and George Washington Jr.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Her oldest brother, Hartley, died of diphtheria shortly after she was born.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] She was raised in a straight-laced, lower-middle-class family during a time when there were limited expectations and opportunities for women.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Her mother had said to her: "I don't know what you expect to do in the world, you're only a girl." From a young age Alice wanted to be an artist, even with little exposure to art.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 1918, after graduating from high school, she took the civil service exam and got a high-paying clerical position in order to help support her parents.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] After three years of work, taking art classes by night in Philadelphia, Neel enrolled in the fine art program at the Philadelphia School of Design for Women (now Moore College of Art & Design) in 1921.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In her student works she rejected impressionism, the popular style at the time, and instead embraced the Ashcan School of Realism.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] It is believed this influence came from one of the most prominent figures of the Ashcan School, Robert Henri, who also taught at Philadelphia School of Design for Women.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] At Philadelphia School of Design for Women, she won honorable mention in her painting class for the Francisca Naiade Balano Prize two years in a row.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 1925 Neel received the Kern Doge Prize for Best Painting in her life class.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] She graduated from Philadelphia School of Design for Women in 1925.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 1924, Neel met Carlos Enríquez, an upper-class Cuban painter, at the Chester Springs summer school run by PAFA.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The couple married on June 1, 1925, in Colwyn, Pennsylvania.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel soon moved to Havana to live with Enríquez's family.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In Havana, Neel was embraced by the burgeoning Cuban avant-garde, a set of young writers, artists and musicians.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In this environment Neel developed the foundations of her lifelong political consciousness and commitment to equality.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel later said she had her first solo exhibition in Havana, but there are no dates or locations to confirm this.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In March 1927, Neel exhibited with her husband in the 12th Salon des Bellas Artes.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] This exhibition also included Eduardo Abela, Víctor Manuel García Valdés, Marcelo Pogolotti, and Amelia Peláez who were all part of the Cuban Vanguardia Movement.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] During this time, she had seven servants and lived in a mansion.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel's daughter, Santillana, was born on December 26, 1926, in Havana.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 1927, though, the couple returned to the United States to live in New York.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Just a month before Santillana's first birthday, she died of diphtheria.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The trauma caused by Santillana's death infused the content of Neel's paintings, setting a precedent for the themes of motherhood, loss, and anxiety that permeated her work for the duration of her career.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Shortly following Santillana's death, Neel became pregnant with her second child.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] On November 24, 1928, Isabella Lillian (called Isabetta) was born in New York City.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Isabetta's birth was the inspiration for Neel's *Well Baby Clinic*, a bleak portrait of mothers and babies in a maternity clinic more reminiscent of an insane asylum than a nursery.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In the spring of 1930, Carlos had given the impression that he was going overseas to look for a place to live in Paris.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Instead, he returned to Cuba, taking Isabetta with him.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] During the time of Enriquez's absence, Neel sublet her New York apartment and traveled to work in the studio of her friends and fellow painters Ethel V.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Mourning the loss of her husband and daughter, Neel had a nervous breakdown, was hospitalized, and attempted suicide.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] She was placed in the suicide ward of the Philadelphia General Hospital.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Deemed stable almost a year later, Neel was released from the sanatorium in 1931 and returned to her parents' home.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Following an extended visit with her close friend and frequent subject, Nadya Olyanova, Neel returned to New York.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] There Neel painted the local characters, including Joe Gould, whom she depicted in 1933 with multiple penises, which represented his inflated ego and "self-deception" about who he was and his unfulfilled ambitions.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The painting, a rare survivor of her early works, has been shown at Tate Modern.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] During the Depression, Neel was one of the first artists to work for the Works Progress Administration.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] At the end of 1933, Neel was offered $30 a week to participate in the Public Works of Art Project (PWAP) during an interview at the Whitney Museum.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] While Neel participated in the PWAP and the Works Progress Administration (WPA)/Federal Art Project, her work gained some recognition in the art world.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] While enrolled in these government programs she painted in a realist style and her subjects were mostly Depression-era street scenes and Communist thinkers and leaders.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Some of these sitters included Mother Bloor, the poet Kenneth Fearing, and Pat Whalen.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] She had an affair with a man named Kenneth Doolittle who was a heroin addict and a sailor.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 1934, he set afire 350 of her watercolors, paintings and drawings.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] At this time, her husband Carlos proposed to reunite, although in the end the couple neither reunited nor officially filed for divorce.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] She consorted with artists, intellectuals, and political leaders of the Communist Party, all of whom became subjects for her paintings.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Her work glorified subversion and sexuality, depicting whimsical scenes of lovers and nudes, like a watercolor she made in 1935, *Alice Neel and John Rothschild in the Bathroom*, which showed the naked pair peeing.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In the 1930s, Neel gained a reputation as an artist, and established a good standing within her circle of downtown intellectuals and Communist Party leaders.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] While Neel was never an official Communist Party member, her affiliation and sympathy with the ideals of Communism remained constant.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In the 1930s, Neel moved to the Spanish Harlem and began painting her neighbors, specifically women and children.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The summer of 1930 was a period in her life that she described "as one of her most productive" because that was when she painted her earliest female nudes.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Initially Neel preferred painting men to women.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] She believed women in art represented a dreary way of life consisting of serving men.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] It was during the time when she felt most vulnerable because of the loss of her children and separation from her husband.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] That autumn she had a nervous breakdown and had to be institutionalized.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel's subject matter changed; she went from painting portraits of ordinary people, family, friends, strangers, and well-known art critics to female nudes.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The female nude in Western art had always represented a "Woman" as vulnerable, anonymous, passive, and ageless and the quintessential object of the male gaze.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Through her use of "expressive line, vibrant palette, and psychological intensity", Neel did not depict the human body in a realistic manner; it was the way she was able to capture and dignify her sitters' psychological and internal standpoint that made the portraits realistic.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] For this reason, many art critics today describe Neel's female nudes as truthful and honest portraits, although at the time the works were controversial in the art world because they questioned women's traditional role.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel often painted women in social interaction or in public spaces, starkly challenging the "Spheres of Femininity" that most 19th-century women artists existed and worked within.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In other words, it is believed that Neel challenged the norms of women's role in the household and in everyday life from her paintings.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel fundamentally changed the way the art establishment viewed the potentialities of the female nude by depicting an unprecedented range of the female experience.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] One of Neel's best known early female nude portraits is of Ethel V.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel depicted Ethel, her friend from the Philadelphia School of Design for Women (now part of Moore College of Art and Design), as many art historians described as "nearly crippled with self conscious by her own exposure".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Ethel's body was exposed in a crouched seated position, where she was able to look the viewer directly in the eye.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Ethel's eyes were commonly described as "soulful" and expressing a sense of fear.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel painted her friend through a distorted scale that added to the idea of "vulnerability and fearfulness".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel said of the image: "She's almost apologizing for living.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The painting was exhibited 43 years later at the Alumni Exhibition, where it was severely criticized by many art critics and the general public.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The reaction that the painting received was a firm dislike as it was thought it was going against the norms of how female nudes were supposed to be depicted.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Ethel, the female nude, saw it on display and "stormed out of rage".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The particular painting of the female nude was neither sexual nor flattering to the female form.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] However, Neel's aim was not to paint the female body in an idealistic way, she wanted to paint in a truthful and honest manner.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] For this reason she thought of herself as a realist painter.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel's second son, Hartley, was born in 1941 to Neel and her lover, the communist intellectual Sam Brody.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] During the 1940s, Neel made illustrations for the Communist publication *Masses & Mainstream*, and continued to paint portraits from her uptown home.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] However, in 1943 the Works Progress Administration ceased working with Neel, which made it harder for the artist to support her two sons.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] During this time, Neel would shoplift and was on welfare to help make ends meet.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Between 1940 and 1950, Neel's art virtually disappeared from galleries, save for one solo show in 1944.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In the 1950s, her friendship with Mike Gold and his admiration for her social realist work garnered her a show at the Communist-inspired New Playwrights Theatre.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 1959, Neel even made a film appearance after the director Robert Frank asked her to appear alongside a young Allen Ginsberg in his beatnik film, *Pull My Daisy*.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The following year, her work was first reproduced in *ARTnews* magazine.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] By the mid-1960s, many of Neel's female friends had become pregnant which inspired her to paint a series of these women nude.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The portraits truthfully highlight instead of hiding the physical changes and emotional anxieties that coexist with childbirth.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel chose to paint the "basic facts of life" and strongly believed that this form of subject matter is worthy enough to be painted in the nudes, which was what distinguished her from other artists of her time.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The pregnant nudes suggested by the art historian, Ann Temkin, allowed Neel to "collapse the imaginary dichotomy that polarizes women into the chaste Madonna or the specter of the dangerous whore" as the portraits were of ordinary women that one sees all around, but not in art.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] One of her works that depicted a pregnant female nude is *Margaret Evans Pregnant* (1978), now in the collection of the Institute of Contemporary Art, Boston.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Margaret was painted while sitting on upright chair that forced her to expose her pregnant stomach even more, which became the central point in the canvas.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Right behind the chair a mirror was placed which allowed the viewer to see the back of her head and neck.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] However, the mirrored reflection did not look anything like Margaret's frontal portrait.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Pamela Allara says Neel has been accurately characterized as a "sort of artist–sociologist who revived and redirected the dying genre of ameliorative portraiture by merging objectivity with subjectivity, realism with expressionism.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel painted Kate Millett in 1970, using photographs of Millett to do so, because Millett had refused to pose for Neel.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Kate Millett was the author of *Sexual Politics*, an important text of second-wave feminism.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Alice Neel's career was given new life by the feminist art movement, and Kate Millett was a feminist icon of the time.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel considered herself "a collector of souls" and she aimed to capture Millett's powerful aura.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel painted this portrait at a time when many independent women, fighting for equal opportunities and being ignored, were looking for a mentor.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In this painting, Kate Millett is directly looking at the viewer, and her stare is very commanding.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Kate Millett was featured in the September 25, 2017 issue of *Time* magazine, in which *Time* referred to her as the "high priestess" of feminism and to *Sexual Politics* as the feminist bible.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel painted herself in her eightieth year of life, seated on a chair in her studio.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] She wore her glasses and held her paintbrush on her right hand and an old cloth on the other hand.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The white color of her hair and the several creases and folds of her bare skin indicated her old age.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] As she painted herself seated on the chair her body faced away from the viewer while head was turned towards the viewer.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The portrait was completed in 1980 but she had started to paint it five years earlier, before abandoning it for a period of time.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] However, she was encouraged by her son Richard to complete it and came back to in her early 80s as she was also invited to take part in an exhibition of self-portraits at the Harold Reed Gallery in New York.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] When Neel's unconventional self-portrait was showcased it attracted considerable attention.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel painted herself in a truthful manner as she exposed her saggy breasts and belly for everyone to see.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Yet again in her last painting, she challenged the social norms of what was acceptable to be depicted in art.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Her self-portrait was one of her last works before she died.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] On October 13, 1984, Neel died with her family present in her New York City apartment, from advanced colon cancer.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Toward the end of the 1960s, interest in Neel's work intensified.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The momentum of the women's movement led to increased attention, and Neel became an icon for feminists.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 1970, she was commissioned to paint the feminist activist Kate Millett for the cover of *Time* magazine.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Millett refused to sit for Neel; consequently, the magazine cover was based on a photograph.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Her image is included in the iconic 1972 poster Some Living American Women Artists by Mary Beth Edelson.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] By the mid-1970s, Neel had gained celebrity and stature as an important American artist.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The American Academy and the Institute of Arts and Letters elected Neel in 1976.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 1979, President Jimmy Carter presented her with a National Women's Caucus for Art award for outstanding achievement.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel's recognition was at its height at the time of her death in 1984.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel's life and works are featured in the documentary *Alice Neel*, which premiered at the 2007 Slamdance Film Festival and was directed by her grandson, Andrew Neel.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] The film was given a New York theatrical release in April of that year.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Her career was used in a 3-episode series of the Freakonomics podcast "The Hidden Side of the Art Market", illustrating that "the art market is so opaque and illiquid that it barely functions like a market at all".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Neel's work was included in the 2022 exhibition *Women Painting Women* at the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 1943, Neel's female nude portrait of Ethel Ashton was exhibited at Alumni Exhibition for the very first time, 13 years after the painting was created, and received brutal criticisms from art critics and the general public.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 1971, Moore College of Art hosted a solo exhibition of alumna Neel's work.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 1974, Neel's work was given a retrospective exhibition at the Whitney Museum of American Art, and posthumously, in the summer of 2000, also at the Whitney.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 1980, she was invited to take part in an exhibition of self-portraits at the Harold Reed Gallery in New York, where her self-portrait was showcased for the first time.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 2001 the Philadelphia Museum of Art organized a retrospective of her art entitled "Alice Neel".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 2004, the first exhibition dedicated to Neel's works in Europe was held in London, at the Victoria Miro Gallery.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Jeremy Lewison, who had worked at the Tate, was the curator of the collection.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 2010, Jeremy Lewison and Barry Walker presented, for Museum of Fine Arts, Houston, *Alice Neel: Painted Truths*, on view from March 21 to June 15, 2010, which later went to the Whitechapel Gallery, London and Moderna Museet Malmö, Sweden.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 2013, the first major presentation of the artist's watercolors and drawings, as *Alice Neel: Intimate Relations*, was on view at Nordiska Akvarellmuseet in Skärhamn, Sweden.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 2016, the Ateneum, Helsinki presented *Alice Neel: Painter of Modern Life*, which later went to the Kunstmuseum Den Haag, The Hague, the Fondation Vincent van Gogh Arles, France, and, in 2018, the Deichtorhallen, Hamburg, Germany, from October 10, 2017, to January 14, 2018.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 2017, Hilton Als curated the exhibition "Alice Neel, Uptown" at the Victoria Miro Gallery in London (May 18 – July 29, 2017).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 2021, a career-spanning retrospective of Neel's work opened at the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] Titled "Alice Neel: People Come First", the exhibit featured more than 100 works and was the largest-ever show of Neel's work in New York and the first in two decades.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] That same year, *Alice Neel: People Come First*, a retrospective of her work, opened at the Guggenheim Bilbao before travelling to de Young Museum in 2022.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 2023, *Alice Neel: Hot Off The Griddle*, the largest exhibition of her work to date in the UK, opened at The Barbican Centre Art Gallery in London.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 2024, *Alice Neel: At Home*, curated by Hilton Als, was the first major exhibition to focus on queer communities and those who were part of her circle, opened at David Zwirner Gallery.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 2015, Xavier Hufkens began representing Neel's estate.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/alice-neel] In 2026, Victoria Newhouse sold *Mother and Child (Nancy and Olivia)*, a 1967 portrait of the artist’s daughter-in-law and first grandchild, for $5.7 million with fees at Christie’s in New York.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The **American Labor Party** (**ALP**) was a political party in the United States established in 1936 that was active almost exclusively in the state of New York.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The organization was founded by labor leaders and former members of the Socialist Party of America who had established themselves as the Social Democratic Federation (SDF).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The party was intended to parallel the role of the British Labour Party, serving as an umbrella organization to unite New York social democrats of the SDF with trade unionists who would otherwise support candidates of the Republican and Democratic parties.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Before and after its demise, many ALP members joined the Liberal Party of New York (LPNY) and the Progressive Party.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] On April 1, 1936, Sidney Hillman, John L.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Meanwhile, the Socialist Party of America suffered an internal struggle between the right-wing Old Guard and left-wing.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] In May 1936, the Old Guard broke from the party and formed the Social Democratic Federation (SDF), taking *The Forward* with them.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The SDF formed the People's Party in New York.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Max Zaritsky, a union president, suggested forming a political party from the Labor's Non-Partisan League of the Congress of Industrial Organizations to David Dubinsky and Sidney Hillman.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The party's name, American Labor Party, was suggested by Nagler.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Antonini was the first state chairman of the party, serving from 1936 until 1942.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] James Farley, chair of the New York State Democratic Committee, and Edward J.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Flynn, chair of the DNC, did not support the party, but Franklin D.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Roosevelt ordered the Democrats to aid the ALP in collecting enough signatures for party status.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] During the summer of 1936, the New York state organization of LNPL was transformed into an independent political party in an effort to bolster Roosevelt's electoral chances in the state by gaining him a place on a second candidate ballot line.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] 274,924 voted for Roosevelt using the ALP's ballot line in the 1936 presidential election, with 238,845 coming from New York City.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The largest amount of support came from Jewish areas.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The organization was largely funded by the needle trade unions of the state.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The ALP found itself $50,000 in debt at the end of the 1936 campaign, but substantial contributions from labor groups erased the red ink.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The ILGWU itself contributed nearly $142,000 to the 1936 campaign, a relatively huge sum for a third party campaign, given that only $26,000 from all sources had been raised and spent by Norman Thomas' Socialist campaign in the previous presidential election.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Over 200 unions were affiliated with the ALP by 1937.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Party decision-making in the first year was handled by ILGWU executive secretary Fred Umhey, the Amalgamated Clothing Workers Union's Jacob Potofsky, and Alex Rose of the Milliners'.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The party supported Fiorello La Guardia during the 1937 New York City mayoral election and he received 482,790, 21.6% of the popular vote, on their ballot line.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] They were the second-largest party in the city and largest in some districts in the Bronx and Brooklyn.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Members of the Communist Party USA started joining the party and Israel Amter, chair of the Communist Party, called for the "building of the American Labor Party".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Although its constitution specifically barred Communists from the organization, there was no enforcement for this provision and large numbers flocked to registration as ALP members from the Communist-led United Electrical Workers, Transport Workers, and State, County, and Municipal Workers.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Norman Thomas and the Socialists attempted to enter the party in 1937, but faced opposition.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Algernon Lee opposed their entrance due to Thomas' pacifism.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Communists in the ALP opposed reelecting Roosevelt in the 1940 presidential election and the party's leadership started an attempt to remove them from the party.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The party condemned the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Fights broke out at the party's convention on September 14, 1940, where Roosevelt was given the nomination despite an attempted resolution condemning Roosevelt.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Labor activists Victor Alter and Henryk Ehrlich were executed by the Soviets.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Anti-communists in the ALP condemned their deaths while communists defended the Soviet Union.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Vito Marcantonio was also a supporter of the Soviet Union.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] This debate was one of the major issues in the party's county committee elections in 1943, and the left-wing gained control over the Bronx affiliate.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Hillman, a member of the left-wing, threatened to have the ACWA become involved in the 1944 state committee elections if the party's leadership voted against a proposal to increase union control over the party.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Berle and Eleanor Roosevelt supported the party's right-wing while Franklin Roosevelt wanted to avoid conflict between the factions.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] La Guardia proposed a compromise in which the state executive committee would be divided between the factions and no communist would be on the election slate.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Hillman accepted the proposal, but Dubinsky rejected it.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The left-wing won 620 of the 750 committee seats.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The Liberal Party of New York was formed in opposition to the ALP by Paul Blanshard, August Claessens, Harry W.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The passage of the Wilson Pakula prevented candidates from the ALP from being able to run for the nominations of other parties without the approval of the party's committee.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The party lost two state legislators in the 1948 election, but Marcantonio was able to win reelection solely on the American Labor ballot line.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] O'Leary was appointed New York State Comptroller by Governor Herbert H.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Lehman both to recognize the ALP's previous and to maintain the party's future support.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] In 1944 the Congress of Industrial Organization's Greater New York Industrial Union Council, a federation of unions in New York City, formally linked itself to the ALP.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] On October 9, 1947, Charles Rubinstein, president of the United Civic Associations of the Bronx, member of the ALP's State executive committee, and former ALP candidate for the City Council left the ALP for no other party, due to "misguided Communist sympathizers" within the ALP.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Wallace's position on the Soviet Union after he was dismissed from President Harry S.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Vito Marcantonio supported giving the party's presidential ballot line to Wallace while Jacob Potofsky opposed it and left the party in protest.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Wallace previously rejected third-party politics at a speech before the ALP on May 25, 1946, when he stated that "because of the election laws in any states, it would give a reactionary victory by dividing the votes of the progressives".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The CIO called for all of its ALP-affiliated unions to disaffiliate and ACWA withdrew its support of the ALP after the party endorsed Wallace for president.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Mike Quill, president of the Transport Workers Union of America, broke away from the party stating that "the screwballs and crackpots who will continue to carry on as if the Communist Party and the American Labor Party were the same house with two doors".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] In 1948, Tammany Hall formed the United Laborite Party, a paper party, meant to draw votes away from the ALP, but the courts ruled in favor of the ALP and stated that the party violated laws prohibiting similarly named parties.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Marcantonio won a seat again to the United States House of Representatives, representing East Harlem for the ALP, as he had done in 1938, 1940, 1942, 1944, and 1946 (but lost in 1950).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Marcantonio had been the target of the New York Wilson Pakula Act in 1947 aimed at restricting candidates from one party running in another party's primary election (electoral fusion).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Leo Isacson was elected in early 1948 to fill a vacancy in a Bronx district but lost in the general election in November.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The Communist Party USA openly endorsed the Progressive Party; some ALP candidates that year were known or alleged communists, e.g., Lee Pressman.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] In 1949, Marcantonio was the ALP nominee for mayor of New York City, marking the first time they fielded an independent candidate for the office.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Although he received endorsements from former vice president Henry A.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Wallace and singer Paul Robeson, Marcantonio came in third place with 14% of the vote.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] The party lost its ballot access after John T.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] McManus, their 1954 gubernatorial candidate, received less than 50,000 votes.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Marcantonio criticized communists for being the reason behind the party's poor performance.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] He claimed that the party's poor performance was due to their poor performance in the 1953 New York City mayoral election.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] He claimed that communists sabotaged the mayoral campaign by implying that they approved voting for the Liberal candidate.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] Marcantonio lost reelection in the 1950 election.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/american-labor-party] He resigned as chair and left the party in November 1953, due to disputes with Communist leaders who he claimed were no longer interested in third-party politics.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The **Russell Sage Foundation** is an American non-profit organisation established by Margaret Olivia Sage in 1907 for “the improvement of social and living conditions in the United States.” It was named after her recently deceased husband, railroad executive Russell Sage.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The foundation dedicates itself to strengthening the methods, data, and theoretical core of the social sciences to better understand societal problems and develop informed responses.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] It supports visiting scholars in residence and publishes books and a journal under its own imprint.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] It also funds researchers at other institutions and supports programs intended to develop new generations of social scientists.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The foundation focuses on labor markets, immigration and ethnicity, and social inequality in the United States, as well as behavioral economics.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The Russell Sage Foundation was established in 1907 for "the improvement of social and living conditions in the United States" by a gift of $10 million from Margaret Olivia Slocum Sage (1828–1918), widow of railroad magnate and financier Russell Sage.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Soon after its establishment, the Foundation played a pioneering role in dealing with problems of the poor and the elderly, in efforts to improve hospital and prison conditions, and in the development of social work as a new profession in the early 20th century.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The Foundation was also responsible for early reforms in health care, city planning, consumer credit, labor law, the training of nurses, and social security programs.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] In 1907, the foundation funded the Pittsburgh Survey, the first systematic effort to survey working-class conditions in a large U.S. city.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Considered a major Progressive Era achievement, the findings inspired labor reforms and helped end twelve-hour days and seven-day weeks for steel workers.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] During this period, the foundation supported a number of prominent female researchers, such as Mary van Kleeck and Lilian Brandt.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Between 1909 and 1922, the Foundation spent nearly a sixth of its capital to build Forest Hills Gardens, a model suburban community for working families designed by architect Frederick Law Olmsted in Queens, New York.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The aim was to demonstrate the economic and social viability of an intelligently planned suburban community.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The first lots sold for $800, and a new suburb began thriving by 1917.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] But with the growth of the New York metro area, housing prices in the new development soon soared beyond the reach of the families they were intended for.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] In 1922, the Foundation helped launch the Regional Plan Association to research, write and publish a plan to guide the future development of the New York metropolitan region.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] In its first 40 years, the Foundation spent more than $1 million on the Regional Survey and Plan.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Researchers completed 12 massive volumes as part of the effort, with the first being published in 1928–29.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The RPA was not opposed to the growth of the area and its population, but believed that for the development to be efficient and orderly, it had to be properly managed; only in this way could businesses continue to grow and the city maintain its global influence.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The Foundation also provided support for social feminists such as Mary van Kleeck, founder of the International Industrial Relations Institute.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Van Kleeck headed up the Foundation's Department of Industrial Studies for four decades, becoming a passionate socialist as a result of her work and research.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Since World War II, the Foundation has devoted its efforts to strengthening the social sciences as a means of achieving more informed and rational social policy.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] It launched a variety of programs to draw the social sciences closer to decision-makers in other professions, from policymakers to health care providers.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] This initiative included funds for research on "social indicators", a collection of data that measure the quality of life.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Mary Van Kleeck, who headed the foundation in the late 1940s, was also a member of the American Labor Party.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] She served on a committee for the Progressive Party in 1948.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] In the 1950s, the Foundation supported research on the practice and aims of philanthropy.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] It established the Foundation Center, a non-profit that maintains data on organized philanthropy.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] It was also the first to publish *The Foundation Directory*, a comprehensive listing of the nation's several thousand largest foundations.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] During this decade, the foundation also received money from the Ford Foundation ($554,000) to support research in the "practical utilization of the behavioral sciences".
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] In the 1960s and 1970s, the Foundation turned to exploring issues in medical ethics, including patients' rights, the rationale of extreme measures to sustain life that were possible with new technology, and the use of human subjects in research.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Foundation-supported books from this period include Bernard Barber's *Drugs and Society* (1967) and *The Dying Patient* (1970).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The Foundation was an early force in the development of behavioral economics, launching the Behavioral Economics program in 1986 with the Alfred P.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Books on behavioral economics published by Russell Sage include *Quasi Rational Economics* (1991) and *Advances in Behavioral Finance* (1993).
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] In 1993, the Foundation also established the Behavioral Economics Roundtable, a group of behavioral economists elected by grantees in the program and charged to design initiatives to advance the field.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Three charter members of the Roundtable subsequently received the Nobel Prize in economics: George Akerlof, Daniel Kahneman, and Thomas Schelling.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The Foundation launched new programs to study immigration, the rise of economic inequality, and contact among cultures within the American population.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Between 1992 and 2000, the Foundation worked with the Ford Foundation to conduct a Multi-City Study of Urban Inequality.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] In 2000, the Foundation partnered with the Population Reference Bureau (PRB) to produce *The American People: Census 2000*, edited by Reynolds Farley of the University of Michigan and John Haaga of PRB.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] From 2014 to 2016, the Foundation entered into research collaborations with a number of other foundations on a variety of topics related to its core interests.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Co-funders include the Carnegie Corporation; the William T.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Kellogg Foundation; the MacArthur Foundation; the Spencer Foundation; and the Washington Center for Equitable Growth.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] In 2015 the Foundation partnered with the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation on an initiative exploring the social, economic and political effects of the Affordable Care Act.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Also in 2015, the Foundation launched *RSF: The Russell Sage Foundation Journal of the Social Sciences*, a peer-reviewed, open-access journal of social science research.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The Foundation publishes books on a variety of subjects, with particular emphasis on work related to its programs.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] George Award from the International Society of Political Psychology.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The Foundation also publishes *RSF: The Russell Sage Foundation Journal of the Social Sciences*, a peer-reviewed, open-access journal of social science research.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The Foundation publishes the American Sociological Association’s distinguished Rose Series in Sociology.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Its publications are distributed by the Chicago Distribution Center.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The Russell Sage Foundation has established a center where Visiting Scholars can pursue their writing and research.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Each year, the Foundation invites a number of scholars to its New York City headquarters to investigate topics in social and behavioral sciences.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The Foundation particularly welcomes groups of scholars who wish to collaborate on a specific project during their residence at Russell Sage.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Typically Visiting Scholars work on projects related to the Foundation's current programs.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] In 2015, the Foundation established a Visiting Journalists program to support journalists undertaking original research on social, political, and economic conditions in the United States.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The Foundation also established the Margaret Olivia Sage Scholars program, which provides the opportunity for distinguished social scientists to spend brief periods in residence at the Russell Sage Foundation, in 2015.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] On an occasional basis, the Foundation considers applications for short-term fellowships by scholars who are conducting research relevant to the Foundation's priority areas through its Visiting Researchers program.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The Foundation's archives are located in the Rockefeller Archive Center in Sleepy Hollow, New York.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] When the Foundation was formed, it attempted to locate its offices in the United Charities Building on Park Avenue South and East 22nd Street in Manhattan, but was unable to do so as the building was fully rented; instead, the new foundation spread out to a number of locations in the area.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] DeForest decided to construct a headquarters building for the Foundation which would also serve as a memorial to her late husband.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The building, which was originally nine stories before a penthouse was added in the 1920s, was constructed between 1912 and 1913 and altered in 1922–1923.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] A fifteen-story extension on East 22nd, which Atterbury also designed, connected to the original building with a five-story "hyphen", was added between 1930 and 1931.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Atterbury's design took the form of a Renaissance Florentine palazzo.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Because it was both headquarters for the Foundation and a physical memorial for Sage, the building was more opulently constructed than would generally be the case for a charity.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Atterbury utilized expensive materials in the interior, such as rare Kingwood sandstone in the elevators.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The 1922-1923 alteration added second floor sculptural panels by Rene Paul Chambellan illustrating the foundation's ideals, goals and deeds.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The Foundation made available space in the main building, at no charge, to other social-service organizations, such as the Family Welfare Association of America, the American Association of Social Workers and the Library of Social Work, which took up the top two floors of the main building.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Space in the 22nd Street extension was rented out, and the New York School of Social Work was the primary tenant.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The Foundation sold the building in 1949 to the Archdiocese of New York which used it as the headquarters of Catholic Charities, and it was sold again in 1975, after which it was converted to apartments; it is now called **Sage House**.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The building was designated a New York City landmark in 2000, and is part of a proposed extension to the Gramercy Park Historic District.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] Since 1981, the Foundation has been headquartered in a Philip Johnson-designed International Style building at 112 East 64th Street between Park and Lexington Avenues, built in 1958-1960 for the Asia Society and Japan Society.
[src:russell-sage-foundation/russell-sage-foundation] The building is in the Upper East Side Historic District.
